<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Officers Expelled for Pro-Islamic Tendency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 24 officers have been
expelled from the Turkish Armed Forces for their inclination
toward Islamism, the Daily News newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Their discharge was in line with a decision made at the Supreme
Military Council (SMC) meeting, which started Monday.
</P>
<P>
These officers were allegedly involved in fundamental and other
illegal activities, informed sources, who asked not to be named,
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's powerful military has always kept the armed forces
under tight control in order to prevent the infiltration of
Islamic thoughts.
</P>
<P>
Every year a different number of officers are discharged from
the army due to similar reasons, which sets off criticism by human
rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
The SMC meeting, which will end Thursday, is to decide on the
promotion of top military officers, including the post of chief of
general staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
