<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Announces Measures to Boost Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government announced
Wednesday a special package of measures to revive sagging exports
by slashing interests on pre- and post-shipment credit and
allowing legal undertakings instead of bank guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the package in Lok Sabha, the lower house of
Parliament, Commerce Minister Ramakrishna Hegde said that special
temporary facility of reduction in pre- and post-shipment credit
to nine percent from 11 percent would be available for the whole
of the current financial year.
</P>
<P>
The package was worked out jointly by the ministries of
commerce and finance after a series of meetings which reviewed the
declining trends in exports in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Hegde said that effecting from September 1, this year, the
government would pay interest to exporters if duty drawback dues
or refund of terminal excise duty was delayed beyond two months.
</P>
<P>
The facility of legal undertakings instead of bank guarantees
at present given to customs as a security for import of duty-free
raw materials would be provided to manufacturer-exporters to
tackle the problem of procedural delays.
</P>
<P>
The commerce minister extended the tax holiday to export
oriented units and export processing zones from the present five
to 10 years, permitted subcontracting facility to export oriented
units in domestic tariff area and allowed export through couriers.
</P>
<P>
He also extended the benefit of export promotion capital goods
(EPCG) scheme to private software technology parks and said
specified technology and small scale engineering industry would be
entitled to zero-duty EPCG scheme under the 10 million rupee
threshold limit.
</P>
<P>
During the financial of 1997-98, India's exports were valued at
33.98 billion U.S. dollars while imports were valued at 40.779
billion U.S. dollars, indicating a trade deficit of 6.799 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted last month by the Confederation
of Indian Industry's Council, the first quarter of 1998-99
witnessed a negative growth rate in 93 industry sectors, including
automobile, steel, cement and capital goods.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry said India's exports have been hit by the
sluggishness in international trade and currency crisis in the
Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Due to sharp depreciation of the currencies of these countries,
said the annual report of the ministry for 1997-98 released in
July, not only has India's competitiveness vis-a-vis these
countries been affected but also direct exports from India to the
Southeast Asian region have suffered badly.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Herald daily, since the Bharatiya
Janata Party (BJP) came to power in March, foreign institutional
investors have withdrawn 450 million U.S. dollars, foreign
exchange reserves have come down by 1.6 billion U.S. dollars and
exporters' orders have been canceled by several industrialized
countries.
</P>
<P>
This, the paper said, might lead to widening of trade deficit
to around 10 billion U.S. dollars this year and there is no chance
to achieve the planned target of 20 percent growth rate in
exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
