<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-05 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Wants Full Diplomatic Ties with Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has asked for upgrading
diplomatic relations with Egypt and reopening embassies in both
Cairo and Baghdad after seven years of icy ties, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Sherif Reehan, head of the Egyptian Interest Section in
Baghdad, told the Egyptian news agency from Baghdad Wednesday that
the request came at a recent meeting between him and Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Aziz lauded the improvement of bilateral
ties, and said the recent visits by Egyptian Trade Minister Ahmed
Goweili and Health Minister Ismail Sallam to Baghdad helped
promote trade relations, Reehan added.
</P>
<P>
Sallam visited Baghdad last month at the head of a 50-member
delegation and personally undertook three surgeries for Iraqi
cardiac patients.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi ministers of industry and health are expected to visit
Cairo in the coming few weeks, the Egyptian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-Baghdad relations were virtually cut off during the
1991 Gulf War when Egypt joined the U.S.-led multi-national forces
to drive Iraq out of Kuwait. However they have since tried to keep
their diplomatic ties at the level of councillorship.
</P>
<P>
Last year Iraq purchased from Egypt medicines, mostly
antibiotics, worth 14 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of 1998, Egyptian exports to Iraq
reached 203 million dollars, and are expected to top 250 million
dollars for the whole year. Most of the Egyptian exports are
pharmaceuticals and foodstuffs within the framework of the
oil-for-food program of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iraq-U.N. deal struck in 1996, Iraq is permitted to
sell a limited amount of oil every six months to import food,
medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception of the crippling economic sanctions
the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
While some Egyptian firms inked deals with Baghdad to increase
food and medical exports, others have offered to participate in
schemes to develop Iraq's dilapidated oil sector and prospect for
new oil fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
