<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Females More Likely to Suffer AIDS: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Females are morely likely to be
infected with AIDS than males because of cultural as well as
social and economic reasons, an AIDS official told Xinhua here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Aknne Nakaweesi, an administration and advocacy coordinator
with Uganda AIDS Commission, said that of the 49,432 adult cases
recorded till December 1997, 26,104 were females, accounting for
54 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Jane Kanyunyuzi, a documentation and information coordinator
there, said in the age group 15-19 years, girls are six times
more likely to be infected than boys in the same age group.
</P>
<P>
They both agreed that there are many reasons for the result.
But cultural and socio-economic reasons are the major ones.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, male superiority is nationally observed. And there
are many girls of this age drop out of school to save fees for
their brothers because families cannot afford all the children's
school fees. These dropouts are very likely to take to
prostitution, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Young girls are deemed as safe and therefore they are often
victims of rapes and defilements.
</P>
<P>
Polygamy and inheritage of widows are also held partially
responsible for the spread of the pandemic. The number of wives
is an indicator of the husband's wealth and social status.
</P>
<P>
Widows are traditionally encouraged to remain in the families
by being inherited by her brothers-in-law. This is the best way
to guarantee her kids are better protected and their livelihood
is secured.
</P>
<P>
It is very difficult for the widow to remarry and have her
kids properly protected, they added. In that case, the kids would
suffer discrimination as a result.
</P>
<P>
The notion of family lineage, clan and tribe is stressed.
Although widows can choose to remarry, most of them usually
prefer to be inherited within the big family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
