<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Delegation to Mediate Crisis in Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) is to send a delegation to Guinea Bissau
soon to meet with parties of the conflict in the
Portuguese-speaking country.
</P>
<P>
This was agreed on at a one-day meeting of representatives of
the ECOWAS Committee of Seven on Guinea Bissau Tuesday in Accra,
Ghana, according to a report reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by foreign ministers of Burkina Faso,
Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Guinea and ambassadors of Nigeria and
Senegal was trying to find a solution to the two-month-old
conflict in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Crisis broke out in Guinea Bissau in early June when dismissed
Chief of Army Staff, General Ansumane Mane led a rebellion
against President Joao Bernado Vieira.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Seven was set up in July to mediate the
crisis. It has been mandated to use dialog and negotiations,
imposition of sanctions and enforcement of embargo, and use force
as a last resort to end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued after Tuesday's meeting, the Committee
reaffirmed its objectives in Guinea Bissau, including the
restoration of peace and restitution of the authority of
President Vieira.
</P>
<P>
The committee mentioned the on-going initiative by the
community of Portuguese-speaking countries and welcomed the truce
declared by troops loyal to Vieira and the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
The committee said it was prepared to cooperate with the
community of Portuguese-speaking nations and expressed support for
other initiatives which might contribute to the realization of
ECOWAS objectives in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
It expressed appreciation to the United Nations and other
institutions providing humanitarian assistance to civilian
victims of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS committee reiterated that lasting peace could not
be achieved in Guinea Bissau unless initiatives to resolve the
crisis were undertaken within the context of efforts to safeguard
sub-regional security.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS has earlier rejected a request by Portugal that it
should steer clear of the crisis in Guinea Bissau, saying that if
the former colonial master wants to help, it should do so in
concert with the region where the country is located. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
