<HEADLINE> Greece to Reforest Lands Destroyed by Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Greece decided Wednesday to
reforest hundreds of thousands of acres of forestland destroyed by
raging fires in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Greek firefighters, backed by fireplanes and local residents,
have been battling forest fires which broke out around Athens on
Sunday, but it is difficult for them to put the fires under
control because of the strong winds. Meanwhile, forestry service
officials estimated that the latest wave of fires had destroyed
some 800,000 stremma of forest and bush.
</P>
<P>
Greek Environment, Town planning and Public Works Minister
Costas Laliotis said Wednesday that all areas burnt by fire would
automatically be designated for reforestations.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Agriculture Ministry would finance a massive project
for reforestation and the first step would be to secure the
denuded expanses with mesh to contain land erosion, said Minister
Stephanos Tzoumakas after meeting Prime Minister Costas Simitis,
who returned to Athens Tuesday from his vacation to discuss with
ministers the ways of tackling forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Tzoumakas said that expanses that had burnt for a second time
would undergo artificial reforestation while land burnt for the
first time would be reforested naturally.  
</P>
</TEXT>
