<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Farmers' Earnings Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's commercial farmers
will earn 19 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (about 900 million U.S.
Dollars) from the sale of commodities in the current marketing
year, an increase of eight percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Wednesday at the Congress of Commercial
Farmers' Union (CFU) in Harare by CFU Deputy Director Jerry
Grant.
</P>
<P>
"Of the major commodities grown, good maize prices will almost
double earnings for maize growers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commodities which had done well were paprika and horticulture
which produced more than 60 different types of fruits and
vegetables and a wide range of cut flowers, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Grant said, this year's production was below that of
1996 in real terms due to poor tobacco prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, John Smith, chairman of the Poultry Producers'
Association, said poultry meat production in the formal sector
remained at last year's level while egg production slightly rose.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe would not develop a highly competitive poultry
industry unless it produced sufficient maize, Smith noted.
</P>
<P>
"Given sufficient maize at realistic price, we should become
the dominant poultry producers in the regional markets," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
