<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Presents New Cabinet List to Legislature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ramallah, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
here Wednesday present his new cabinet lineup to the Palestinian
Legislative Council (PLC) and pledged "accountability and
transparency" in all government institutions.
</P>
<P>
Although some new ministers are added to the list, Arafat made
no major changes in the reshuffle and most of the former key
cabinet members retained their presence in the new mix.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Shaath is to stay as the minister of planning and
international cooperation, while Saeb Erekat will retain his post
of minister of local government. The two have been very helpful to
Arafat in conducting peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat appointed new heads to the ministries of labor, industry
and agriculture and he himself maintained power over the Interior
Ministry which controls the Palestinian security forces.
</P>
<P>
He also took over the Education Ministry after relieving the
aging Yasser Amr, placing the ministry under the management of a
committee until new education minister is named.
</P>
<P>
Former ministers of labor, industry and agriculture have been
named ministers without portfolios and will remain in the new
cabinet. Munther Saleh was appointed minister of higher education
to replace Hanan Ashrawi, who was transferred to the portfolio of
tourism and archaeology.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also announced in the lineup three new ministries -
environment, parliamentary affairs and prisoners affairs - to be
headed by Yousef Abu Safieh, Nabil Amro and Hisham Abdul Razeq
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Before presenting his new cabinet list, Arafat addressed the
legislature about the situation in the territories and the current
development of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The platform of this new government is to continue building
Palestinian institutions, and reinforce law and order and the
foundations of an independent judiciary, pluralism, accountability
and transparency in all institutions of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
On the peace process, he said that no progress was made in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and the main reason for that is
Israel's intransigent policy.
</P>
<P>
he called on the U.S. to bear its responsibility pertaining the
peace process and officially announce its initiative requesting
Israel to withdraw from an additional 13.1 percent of the West
Bank in the second stage troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also urged the international community to take
immediate measures to pressure Israel to fulfill its obligations
toward peace and halt all activities which violate the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He called for reinforcing national unity for the purpose of
succeeding with the decision to be taken on May 4, 1999 - the
declaration of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The presentation of the new cabinet lineup received mixed
reactions. Shaath told Xinhua shortly after Arafat's announcement
that he believed the new team represented "a new, right direction"
for the Palestinian people and the new ministers have the
capability to improve management efficiency as required by the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
But several lawmakers from other factions said this new
cabinet formulation does not meet the demands of the legislature
and the changes are insufficient.
</P>
<P>
Last year the PLC had accused Arafat's former cabinet members
of corruption and inefficiency, which led to 16 cabinet ministers'
offering to resign last August to pave the way for Arafat to
reshuffle the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In June this year, the lawmakers threatened to table the first
no-confidence vote against the PNA. On June 24, Arafat accepted
the resignation of the cabinet and has since conducted political
consultations with different parties over the formation of a new
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The legislature is to debate on the new cabinet line before
reaching a final decision, but no date was set to vote on the new
lineup. Endiem


05/08/98 17:8 GMT

NNNN
01:17 01:18 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
