<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reactions Differ as Khat Dealers on Strike in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Somali capital and its
surrounding regions have been without the narcotic leaves known
as khat for the third day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to khat business dealers, the absence of the
stimulant leaves from Mogadishu's markets followed a seven-day
general strike by main khat importers.
</P>
<P>
One of the importers said the strike was prompted by a serious
misunderstanding between the Somali business dealers and khat
growers in Kenya for supplying them with the poorest quality
stuff on the highest price.
</P>
<P>
"They send the best quality type to Europe and to the Gulf
countries while the residue is always sent to us," lamented Ahmed
Ali, one khat seller in Black Sea Market of the capital, adding
"we can no longer tolerate this."
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of the khat selling kiosks in Mogadishu were closed
down making hundreds of their dependents jobless.
</P>
<P>
A large number of tea shops alongside the main streets are now
complaining about less income following the start of the strike.
</P>
<P>
"We have to close down our business early in the evening...
since there are no khat chewing youngsters to accommodate,"
protested a lady running a tea shop.
</P>
<P>
Even though the strike had been on full scale, there are still
a few dealers who are bringing a very small amount of the drug in
an underground way. Each bundle of the khat (about 0.5 kg) which
was sold earlier at less than 20,000 Somali Shillings (nearly 2.5
Dollars) is now sold at more than 100,000 Shillings (about 12.5
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The absence of the narcotic leaves are beneficial in another
aspect. Hundreds or perhaps thousands of addicted armed
militiamen are now behaving themselves and reacting normally to
the daily occurrences.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, when high on the drug the gunmen especially those on
the battle wagons would shoot at people whenever they come across
a traffic jam, rather than using the vehicle horns.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, economists and health authorities are applauding
the strike and calling for a total ban on khat imports.
</P>
<P>
While doctors believe that the use of the narcotic leaves
brings about multiple social problems including health hazards,
impotence for men which put an end to numerous marriages every
month. Economists argue that the khat is seriously hurting the
already poor economy of the country.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 U.S. Dollars are spent on khat imports
everyday. More than 15 small Cesna planes fly the stimulant
leaves from Kenya to many parts of the country including
Mogadishu, Kismaio, Bolotuein, Galkaio, Hargeisa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
