<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-05 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliament Calls for Ending Cooperation With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi parliament on Wednesday
called on the government to stop cooperation immediately with the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq, known as UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The 250-member National Assembly adopted a resolution
unanimously on Wednesday's special session, urging the government
to sever relations with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The resolution came after disarmament talks between UNSCOM and
Iraq broke down on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the conclusion of a special session,
the Assembly says lawmakers believe that UNSCOM will never give
Iraq a clean bill of health on its weaponry.
</P>
<P>
The statement criticizes UNSCOM for creating pretexts to
prolong sanctions on Iraq, which serves the U.S. anti-Iraq policy.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM verifies that it has
destroyed its chemical, biological weapons and long-range
missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly's statement calls for Iraqi leaders to take
necessary measures to safeguard its national interests, pledging
"full support" for any measures that President Saddam Hussein
takes.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly's resolution needs to be approved by the powerful
Revolutionary Command Council, with Saddam as chairman of the
decision-making body, but it paves the way for any possible
measures Iraqi leaders might take.
</P>
<P>
The statement also calls for the United Nations Security
Council to lift the sanctions, citing Iraq has fulfilled all its
obligations under relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared many times that it is free of prohibited
weapons, and accused UNSCOM of pursuing procrastination policy by
focusing on trivial, minor problems to waste time and prolong
work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
