<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran announced on Wednesday that its foreign debts
have declined to 12.117 billion U.S. dollars by the end of last
Iranian year (March 21) from 16.835 dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Iran News quoted a report from the Central Bank of
Iran (CBI) as saying that included 3.289 billion dollars in
short-term debts and 8.828 billion dollars in medium and long-term
debts.
</P>
<P>
If contingent obligations, including opened letters of credit
not yet consigned and future interest are taken into account,
Iran's total external obligations amounted to 24.4 billion
dollars at the end of the year, the CBI report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Iran's external debt in the current Iranian year
would add up to 6.936 billion dollars, including 82 million
dollars for reschedulings under reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said Iran enjoyed a favorable trade balance of 3.511
billion dollars in the past Iranian year, and its liquidity stood
at almost 448 million dollars calculated according to the official
exchange of 3,000 rials against one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Iran's petro-dollars reached 18.5 billion dollars in 1996 when
oil prices were above 19 dollars per barrel, enabling the country
to repay some of its foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said earlier that the country's foreign debts declined
from 22 billion dollars in March 1995 to 16.835 billion dollars in
March 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian sugar stock has surmounted consumption by
two-folds as local production of the sweet commodity has this year
hit 1.23 million tonnes in addition to another 1 million tonnes in
imports.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 1.5 million tons of sugar was imported, and part of
sugar supplies imported from foreign producers is bought sometimes
at less than cost prices.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has succeeded for the first time in paying in full the
536 million pounds (157.7 million U.S. dollars) in dues to farmers
growing sugar cane before July 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is considering imposition of penalties to fight
dumping of certain commodities in the local market, the Middle
East News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial meeting Tuesday looked into a report on confirmed
dumping of match boxes from India and Pakistan into the Egyptian
market.
</P>
<P>
A dumping margin of 46.42 percent and 31.1 percent will be
levied on imported match boxes from India and Pakistan
respectively in accordance with a ministerial decree.
</P>
<P>
Three ministerial decrees have been passed to fight dumping and
protect national industry from protectionist and dumping policies
by foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Commodities in question include rolled iron from Ukraine,
reinforcing iron from Romania and Ukraine and stainless steel
basins from Spain and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
