<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese construction materials company Sodap, the
country's biggest one of its kind, has recently started
cooperation with French cement producer Lafarge in building a
joint venture factory in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star said on Tuesday the 7,500-square-meter new
factory will begin operating in February next year and cost less
than 3 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Its yearly production capacity is divided into three large
parts - a powder workshop with an output of 50,000 tonnes, a paste
workshop, 5,000 tonnes and a liquid workshop, 7,500 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Deposits in Egyptian banks have increased by 16
billion Egyptian pounds, but foreign reserves in the Central Bank
of Egypt (CBE) diminished since May 1997, according to a monthly
statistical bulletin released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deposits, including government deposits, amounted to
211.818 billion Egyptian pounds (some 62 billion U.S. dollars)
last May, compared to 195.793 billion (some 57.6 billion dollars)
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The CBE bulletin noted that net international reserves with the
CBE last May were 20.157 billion dollars, compared with 20.199
billion dollars in the same period last year, down by 42 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate in May 1998 was 3.6 percent, down from 4.9
percent a year earlier. Discount and interest rates remained
unchanged at 12.25 percent throughout.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian mobile telecommunications provider,
Mobinil, has signed 400-million-Egyptian-pound contracts with
Motorola and Alcatel companies for the expansion of Egypt's mobile
communications network.
</P>
<P>
The company's president, Osman Sultan, said Wednesday the new
investments would expand the telephone network to key areas in the
country which have not been covered by the service and will also
improve, enhance and expand services in Cairo and Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
To ensure an advanced service, the company was seeking the
technology of the two leading American and French companies as
partners, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 110,000 Egyptians subscribe to the service and
the newly signed contracts will see an additional 50,000 new
subscribers by the end of August and a planned capacity in excess
of 300,000 subscribers by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The contracts will include the upgrading of the existing
facilities. Motorola and Alcatel will provide the necessary
communications and switching equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
