<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity Returns to Industries in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Electric power has fully returned
to all industrial consumers across Ghana after months of
rationing, while scheduled blackouts have been eased for some
domestic users, according to a report reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The development follows completion of the 30-megawatt Tema
Thermal Power Station, which will compensate for insufficient
output from the Asosombo Hydro-electric Plant where water levels
remain below the minimum required to drive all the turbines.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Ghana's leading newspaper Times as
saying that the information was given to Mauritanian President
Mabuya Ould Sid'Ahmed Taya, who completes a three-day official
visit to Ghana Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Excess electricity from industrial consumers will be used to
provide some communities with three continuous days of power at a
time, according to the Electricity Company of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, domestic users have had to put up with
alternating 12- or 24-hour periods of supply and blackout.
</P>
</TEXT>
