<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Suspends Cooperation With U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 5 (Xinhua) -- In one of the strongest efforts
by Iraq to see the eight-year-old U.N. sanctions on it lifted,
President Saddam Hussein on Wednesday decided to suspend
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
He made the decision soon after a parliament special session
called on the Iraqi leaders to stop cooperation with the
U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said the president decided to
"completely suspend" cooperation with both the U.N. Special
Commission on disarming Iraq, known as UNSCOM, and the
International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made when Iraq has repeated several times that
the sanctions must be lifted in the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, the sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait can not be lifted if U.N. inspectors do not verify that
the country is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of UNSCOM-Iraq talks on the issue collapsed
last Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
