<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-05 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killing of Settlers Underlines Israeli Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Wednesday condemned the killing of two Jewish settlers
as serious crime, saying it proved the necessity of making
security arrangement in the current talks over the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
"I think this was a very, very serious crime," Netanyahu said
at his office. The killing underlined Israel's concern about
security and reaffirmed Israel's insistence that the Palestinians
should take every measure to fight terrorism, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two Jewish settlers were ambushed and killed early
Wednesday as they patrolled their settlement near the West Bank
town of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
"The building of houses, the building of homes for young
couples is not a reason for terror, not a reason to kill people,"
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
The attackers could "probably" came from the
Palestinian-controlled areas, he said, admitting this had not been
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The incident further proved that it was necessary to make
security arrangement in any deal with the Palestinians concerning
the Israeli pullback from the West Bank, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu had agreed to expand
Itzhar, the settlement where the shootings took place, but not
agreed to build new settlements. Settlement leaders would convene
soon to discuss the expansion, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Munzir Salah, newly-appointed minister of higher education of
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), told reporters in
Ramallah that since the Israeli government carried out a policy
"turning a whole people into desperate people," an explosion was
"inevitable."
</P>
<P>
Salah had been a member of the Palestinian lawmaker dealing
with settlement affairs on behalf of the PNA before he was named
Wednesday to replace Hanan Ashrawi by PNA President Yasser Arafat
as part of the cabinet reshuffle. Ashrawi was appointed minister
of tourism.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, speaking to the Palestinian Legislative Council before
announcing his new cabinet list, said Israel should bear "total
responsibility for the total freeze" of the peace process, warning
that "a total chaos" would occur if the process collapses.
</P>
<P>
He called on the United States to make public its initiative
calling on Israel to pullback its troops from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have rejected the latest Israeli proposal
during the latest round of talks Monday night, saying it was far
from consistent with the American initiative.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposed that it withdraw from 10 percent of the West
Bank and turn another 3 percent into a "nature reserve" where
Israel would be responsible for the overall security.
</P>
<P>
The killing, which capped frictions and tensions between the
Palestinians and the Israelis over the Jewish settlements, has
prompted calls from Israel's right-wingers for a halt of the
talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Moshe Peled, a member of the Likud coalition in the parliament,
said the killing proved that the Oslo process had bankrupted and
should be stopped.
</P>
<P>
He was echoed by Michael Kleiner, also a member of the Likud
coalition, who said Netanyahu should at least suspended the talks
with the Palestinians till they handed over the attackers to the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Kleiner also urged Netanyahu to drop a plan to free 100
Palestinian prisoners. Netanyahu was reportedly considering the
release as a goodwill gesture to the Palestinians but he himself
said Tuesday that no decision had been taken.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the Palestinians to catch the killers if they
escaped to the Palestinian-controlled areas, Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai insisted that the killing incident was
not connected with the current talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reports said that at a four-member inner cabinet
meeting Wednesday, Netanyahu presented to National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon and Industry and Trade Minister Natan
Sharansky a map drawn by the Defense Ministry showing the areas
Israel planned to yield, but the two ministers expressed their
reservations.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis have repeatedly rejected the Palestinian demand
during their talks that they show the map demonstrating the
locations of the lands they planned to hand over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
