<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarussian Ruble Falls 17 Percent Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Belarussian ruble dropped 17
percent against the U.S. dollar in two days in transactions
between non-resident banks, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The rate plunged to 84,000-88,000 to the dollar on Wednesday,
down from Monday's 74,000-75,000 to the dollar on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The drop was attributed to the country's restrictions on
interbank currency operations and the subsequent downturn in
demand for the Belarussian ruble.
</P>
<P>
Under government regulations, the currency can be remitted to
non-resident banks only for a limited list of imported items,
while on the country's interbank market no deal in U.S. dollars,
German marks or Russian rubles should exceed 1,000 units of those
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Interfax, quoting experts in Minsk, the Belarussian capital,
said the Belarussian ruble could further slide to 90,000 against
the dollar before the end of week, less than half of the official
rate of 42,450 set on Wednesday by the National Bank of Belarus
(NBB).
</P>
<P>
However, the NBB was confident of its control over the
country's currency market.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the NBB said gold and currency assets of
the central bank and Finance Ministry total 630 million U.S.
dollars "enough to control the situation on the currency market,"
Interfax reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
