<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Portugal Agree to Discuss East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Portugal
have agreed to discuss giving autonomy to East Timor, their
foreign ministers said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Appearing before the press after two days of talks sponsored by
the United Nations, the ministers said in a communique that they
agreed to "hold in-depth discussions on Indonesia's proposals for
a special status, based on a wide-ranging autonomy" for East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Foreign Minister Ali Alatas and his Portuguese
counterpart Jaime Gama, also agreed to "involve the East Timorese
more closely in the search for a solution" to the East Timor
question.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to continue consideration of the issues relating to
Indonesia's intention to further gradually reduce the level of its
military presence in East Timor and to expedite the release of the
East Timorese political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said their two countries agreed to establish
interest sections in friendly embassies in each other's capitals
by the end of 1998 and to relax their visa policies towards each
other's nationals.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have had no diplomatic relations since
Indonesia's takeover of East Timor in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The talks on autonomy, "without prejudice" to the two
countries' "basic positions of principle," will be held by their
senior officials with the hope that "an agreement could be reached
on this issue before the end of this year."
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who held meetings in New
York with the ministers on Tuesday and today, described the
agreements as "a progress, if not a breakthrough".
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with an area of 18,889 square km and a population of
800 thousand, was a former Portuguese colony. In 1976 it became a
province of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly in a resolution adopted in 1977
rejected the claim that East Timor has been integrated into
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The autonomy, proposed by Indonesia, would allow East Timor full
governance except in the fields of foreign affairs, external
defense and some monetary policies, according to Alatas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
