<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Optimistic About Resumed Talks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Lakhdar Brahimi, the visiting U.
N. special envoy said Wednesday that he was optimistic about the
resumption of peace talks between the government and the rebel
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Brahimi noted here that although the danger of renewed war is
over, the two sides should observe the 1994 Lusaka peace deal and
resume talks as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Ambassador to Angola and also U.S.
representative to Angolan peace process, Donald Steinberg, said
both the government and UNITA have promised to resume talks to
save the peace process from the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Angola becomes tense after UNITA has
re-captured about 90 cities and town it formerly handed over to
the government and its military men allegedly killed about 200 in
the July 21 massacre.
</P>
<P>
To help solve the crisis, Brahimi arrived in Luanda last
Friday to meet Angolan President Eduard dos Santos and UNITA
Chairman Jonas Savimbi on mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. observation mission sources said here Wednesday that
Brahimi has decided to extend his scheduled five-day visit till
Saturday in a bid to meet Dos Santos and Savimbi again. 
</P>
