<HEADLINE> Palestinian Diplomat on Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian diplomat said
here Wednesday that the long-running peace deadlock with Israel
has made it impossible to make a sweeping overhaul of the
Palestinian cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Mohamad Sobeih, Palestine's chief delegate to the Arab League
and secretary of the Palestinian National Council, made the remark
to the Middle East News Agency hours after Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat presented a new cabinet
lineup to Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC).
</P>
<P>
According to the new lineup, there were 10 new faces in the
cabinet while all former ministers but one remained.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih termed the new Palestinian cabinet formation as having
"minimal changes" in ministerial posts.
</P>
<P>
"The formation of the Palestinian government hinges directly on
the position of the peace talks situation with Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the latest round of Palestinian-Israeli talks has
failed in realizing progress as Israel continues to offer "old"
ideas in conflict with the American proposal for another 13.1
percent Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinian side will hold contacts with Arab
countries concerned and brief the American administration on the
outcome of the latest contacts with the Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is trying to make
believe that there is progress and rapprochement between the two
sides," he charged.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih asked the U.S. administration to promptly step in and
formally declare its initiative. The U.S. plan has was accepted by
Palestinians but resisted by Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis started their direct talks in
July 19. Israel proposed to pull out from 10 percent of West Bank
territories, and turn the other 3 percent into a "nature reserve."
This has been rejected by the Palestinians. 
</P>
