<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers in South Lebanon Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting President of the 52nd
United Nations General Assembly Guinadi Audvedenko Wednesday
spoke highly of the role the U.N. peacekeeping force is playing in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. Interim Forces in Lebanon (UNIFIL) is playing
a sacred role in a peace mission, adding the troops also provide
social and humanitarian help to local people.
</P>
<P>
Audvedenko made the remark at the headquarters of the UNIFIL at
Naqoura, a southern boundary town.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping force was established in
1978 following the first Israeli invasion of Lebanon. It was to
help the Lebanese government restore authority over its southern
territory and confirm Israeli withdrawal from the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said he is pleased with the visit to the
troops whose mandate has just been renewed for another six months
by the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Resolution 425 and its related Resolution 426
concerning Lebanon, the term of UNIFIL is extended every six
months under the request of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The previous term expired at the end of July this year.
</P>
<P>
When visiting Quana, a village on the north of the Israeli
occupied south Lebanon where some 106 Lebanese civilians were
killed during an Israeli military operation in April, 1996,
Audvedenko said that Lebanon can never enjoy stability and peace
unless Israel withdraws its troops unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 after two invasions with the claimed aim of
protecting its northern villages from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Audvedenko arrived in Lebanon Monday on a two-day visit during
which he had held talks with Lebanon's top leaders over the
regional situation and the role of UNIFIL in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He is to leave for New York Thursday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
