<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Climb Up Slightly in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Affected by production slips
in aircraft and automobiles, orders to U.S. factories edged only
0.1 percent higher in June, the Commerce Department reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The monthly factory orders totaled a seasonally adjusted 330.5
billion U.S. dollars, according to the department. In May, they
had fallen 2.2 percent, the biggest drop in three years, to a
seasonally adjusted 330.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Factory orders in the second quarter were 0.7 percent lower
than that of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report today, the Labor Department said that
employment remained strong despite the manufacturing slowdown. The
number of first-time applications for unemployment benefits edged
higher last week but still kept at a low level.
</P>
<P>
Except transportation, the manufacturing picture is less gloomy
than the overall situation. Orders increased 1.1 percent in June
following a 1.8 percent decrease the month before.
</P>
<P>
Orders for computer and office equipment jumped 7 percent. They
increased 1.6 percent for industrial machinery, 3.5 percent for
stone, clay and glass products and 6.5 percent for navigation,
medical and other instruments.
</P>
<P>
But orders dropped 21.6 percent for aircraft, exceeding a 16.1
percent drop the month before, and 6.9 percent for automotive
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Overall, orders for durable goods, big-ticket items intended to
last three or more years, slipped 0.1 percent while orders for
non-durable goods rose 0.3 percent, the first increase since
March. Food products and chemicals recorded the largest increases
within non-durables.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments, a measure of current production,
increased 0.3 percent in June to a seasonally adjusted 334.6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders fell for the fourth time in five
months. It declined 0.8 percent to 529.3 billion dollars.
Inventories of unsold goods edged 0.2 percent higher, to 466.6
billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
