<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laboratory Tests Cocaine Addiction Blocker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Human testing is expected to
begin this fall on a drug that appears to block cocaine
addiction in laboratory animals and might have promise for use
against other addictions, The Washington Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Department of Energy's Brookhaven
National Laboratory said Wednesday that the drug gamma
vinyl-GABA, or GVC, could be an improvement over methadone, the
most commonly used antidote to cocaine addiction for three decades.
</P>
<P>
The drug, now used fro treatment of epilepsy in Europe and
Canada, is marketed by Hoechst Marion Roussel, a unit of Hoechst
AG in Germany. Brookhaven researchers became interested in it
because it reduces the level of a brain chemical called
dopamine, which causes the "high" feelings from drugs.
</P>
<P>
Cocaine appears to increase dopamine production. But
laboratory animals given GVG in addition to cocaine retained
normal levels of dopamine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Jobless Claims Edge Higher in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of the U.S. new
applications filed for unemployment benefits increased slightly
last week but remained at a level signaling a plentiful supply of
jobs, the Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Claims rose to a seasonally adjusted 307,000, up from a 15-week
low of 301,000 the week before, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
The figure is well below the 394,000 claims registered for two
consecutive weeks in late June and early July, when workers idled
by the U.S. No. 1 car-maker--- the General Motors strikes which
lasted for nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
A four-week moving average of claims fell to 315,500, down from
337,250 for the four-week period ended a week earlier. It was the
lowest level since mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates that demand for labor remained strong at
midsummer despite a dramatic slowdown in overall economic growth
in the second quarter of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
