<HEADLINE> Flood-Stranded Residents in East China Rescued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two people died and 40,000
residents were stranded in Jiujiang, east China's Jiangxi
Province, when a levee gave way on the evening on August 4.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 houses were destroyed and 7,300 hectares of
farmland and some 4,000 hectares of cotton were inundated.
</P>
<P>
The local government immediately dispatched People's Liberation
Army soldiers and local public security officers and men to the
scene to join in rescue efforts. By 18:00 this evening, the last
batch of the stranded people, number more than 8,000, had been
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of China (RCSC) announced Hong Kong
organizations have donated five million yuan (620,000 US dollars)
to relief efforts in flood-stricken areas, including three million
yuan from the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region and two million yuan from local organizations and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Liu Dewang, an RCSC official, said the money will be used to
purchase food and medical supplies for Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi and
Sichuan provinces. 
</P>
