<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wu Bangguo Visits Traditional Industrial Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China's central government pays
close attention to the reemployment and basic subsistence of
workers declared redundant by state-owned enterprises, as well as
transferring management authority over key coal mines to lower
levels of government and development of petroleum industry,
according to Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo.
</P>
<P>
Wu, also member of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China Central Committee, made the remark during a visit to
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, one of China's
traditional industrial bases, between August 3-6.
</P>
<P>
Wu's visit focused on implementing the State Council's
policy for transferring management authority over key coal mines to
lower levels of government.
</P>
<P>
He said the major difficulty centers on the overproduction of
coal. He said China must control total coal production, downsize
the sectors work force and improve production efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Wu pointed out that transferring management authority over key
coal mines is expected to help the industry overcome present
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
China will adopt measures to close various small and illegal
mines, said Wu, adding that plans calls for increasing subsidies
to provinces and cities facing great difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Wu also held meetings covering the issue of ensuring basic
subsistence for laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
He visited the high-tech development zone at Daqing Oil Field
and stressed that the industry should continue to introduce high
technology and noted that oil prices should be in line with
international market.
</P>
<P>
China's oil industry should strive to achieve its target of 10
billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) in profits in the next five
months of 1998, said Wu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Tax Service Seizes Property of Oil Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Tax Service has
seized the property of three oil companies in a crackdown on
defaulting corporate tax payers.
</P>
<P>
The action against the property and bank accounts of Sidanco,
Onaco and the Eastern Oil Company (EOC) began Wednesday, said
Vladimir Popov, head of the Tax Service's department responsible
for dealing with major taxpayers and the forcible collection of
tax arrears.
</P>
<P>
Popov said bankruptcy procedures will be started for Onaco.
Sidanco and EOC will soon face the same fate, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sidanco's tax debt totals 1.2 billion rubles (about 190 million
U.S. dollars). Onaco's debt stood at 845.8 million rubles (136
million dollars) on August 1. The EOC owes the Tax Service 314.1
million rubles (50.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In July, Russia's oil companies paid 612.1 million rubles (92
million dollars) of tax, less than half of the planned amount of
1.5 billion rubles (242 million dollars), which prompted the Tax
Service to step up pressure.
</P>
<P>
"It is not war, it is the beginning of work," Popov said,
adding that August would be a decisive month for all the oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government has been trying hard to boost revenues
in the face of mounting deficits. The oil companies, usually the
country's largest tax payers, bore the brunt of an offensive
against tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Other measures taken against the oil companies include
restriction of their access to pipelines used for exporting oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Meets Mainland-HK Youth Exchange Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Thursday met
with a group of young people from 21 ethnic minority groups in
China's mainland who are visiting Hong Kong on a cultural exchange
program.
</P>
<P>
A group of local youngsters who are participating in the
exchange program also attended the meeting held at the Government
House.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the young visitors, Tung said that he believed this
kind of activities will help promote better understanding between
young people of the mainland and the SAR.
</P>
<P>
The 46 mainland members come from such ethnic minority groups
as the Mongolian, Tibetan, Manchu, Korean and Yi.
</P>
<P>
The exchange program was jointly organized by the China
Overseas Friendship Association and the Yan Oi Tong, a charity
organization in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The participants took part in a variety of activities,
including seminars and visits. The program runs from August 3 to
10.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic minority groups from the mainland will stage three
shows in Hong Kong to share their singing and dancing talents with
the local community.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the chief executive learnt of the
interesting experience of the local and mainland youngsters gained
through various activities and the ethnic minority groups also
greeted Tung in their own dialects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
