<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore MP Welcomes Call for New Singapore- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Singapore
Parliament Thursday expressed welcome to a call from his Malaysian
counterpart for building new Singapore-Malaysian ties.
</P>
<P>
Tan Cheng Bock, leader of Singapore-Southeast Asia
Parliamentary Group, said to the media, "I fully welcome Lim Kit
Siang's proposal. My colleagues and I will be pleased to take part
in such a conference when we receive the invitation from the
Malaysian Parliament."
</P>
<P>
Tan Cheng Bock was referring to a news report that Malaysian
Member of Parliament Lim Kit Siang called for a full mandate to be
given to "parliamentary delegations of both countries to try to
achieve consensus to build new Malaysia-Singapore ties which could
work closely for the sake of peace, development, democracy and
human rights."
</P>
<P>
Lim Kit Siang was also quoted as saying that "Malaysian
Parliament should officially invite Singapore Parliament to hold
Malaysia-Singapore parliamentary conference where delegations of
both countries were given the mandate to resolve CIQ (customs,
immigration and quarantine) issue and other bilateral issues."
</P>
<P>
Relations between Singapore and Malaysia have been recently
soured over a number of issues including the dispute over
Malaysia's CIQ operation in the Tajong Pagar Railway Station which
is located within Singapore.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Singapore Ministry of Home Affairs
rejected a Malaysian news report saying "Singapore shortens social
visit stay for Malaysians."
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the ministry said, "There has not been any
changes in Singapore's immigration policy in relation to the grant
of social visit passes to foreign visitors. Most foreign visitors
arriving by land are granted 14 days' stay. There may be certain
exceptional cases where visitors are granted fewer than 14 days
due to the 60/90 day rule, which has been enforced since June 1,
1981."
</P>
<P>
The 60/90 day rule allows a Malaysian social visitor to stay in
Singapore up to 60 days in every 90 day period. The purpose of the
60/90 day rule is to prevent foreign workers from circumventing
Singapore's work permit policies and working in Singapore
illegally.
</P>
<P>
The grant of social visit passes to foreign visitors by
Singapore Immigration &AMP; Registration is in no way linked to the
move of the Singapore CIQ from Tajong Pagar to Woodlands Train
Check Point, the ministry explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
