<HEADLINE> HK Young Offenders Achieve Good Results in Exam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Young offenders from four
correctional institutions in Hong Kong have obtained good results
in this year's Hong Kong Certificate of Education Examination
(HKCEE), a spokesman for the Correctional Services Department said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 55 young offenders sat for the 1998 HKCEE where they
took 183 papers covering subjects in mathematics, history,
computer studies, social studies and technical drawings. They
achieved one distinction, 14 credits and 81 passes, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The results of the 1998 HKCEE were officially announced
Thursday. The pass rate for the four institutions was 52.45
percent.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the good results reflect the Correctional
Services Department's efforts to provide every opportunity for
young offenders to learn and equip themselves with knowledge in
preparation for their eventual release back into society.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past few years, with the generous donation from the
Hong Kong Jockey Club Trust Fund, we have been able to provide a
number of sophisticated educational equipment to improve teaching
facilities for inmates," he said.
</P>
<P>
These are just some of the plans in which the department is
developing to further enhance the educational environment for
inmates, the spokesman said. "With academic qualifications, they
stand a better chance of competing for better jobs," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
