<HEADLINE> Russia Expels 30 Foreign Spies in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia expelled 30 foreign
intelligence officers and detained seven Russian nationals who
worked for foreign spy agencies in 1997, the Interfax news agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Security Service (FSB) had exposed more than 400
career agents of foreign special services and others "legitimately
suspected of being affiliated with them", said Alexander
Zdanovich, chief of the FSB Public Relations Center.
</P>
<P>
They were under "strict surveillance," he added.
</P>
<P>
He singled out the FSB's success in foiling attempts by
representatives of Sanam, an Iranian industrial group, to collect
data on Russia's latest advances in space, aviation, nuclear and
laser fields.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the FSB Anti-Terrorism Department thwarted 134
terrorist plots and exposed 34 arms trading gangs, seizing 92
bombs, Zdanovich said.
</P>
<P>
The bombs were intended for use in contract murders and
terrorist activities, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
