<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DECD: Germany Joblessness Still High Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- German unemployment will remain high
despite faster economic growth in 1999, the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) forecast in a report
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 report on Germany, the Paris-based organization
expected German jobless rate, which hit a post-1930s record of
12.6 percent early this year, to fall slightly to 11.1 percent in
1999 from a 1998 average of 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that unemployment in the eastern area of Germany,
officially at 17.4 percent at present, would be particularly high
in the coming year as a result of excessive wages and low
productivity.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that German economic growth would rise to
2.9 percent in 1999, compared to about 2.7 percent this year and
2.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Such growth and unemployment level showed that German economy
was experiencing difficult fiscal adjustment and major structural
change, according to the organization.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, It stressed further reforms in the system of
taxation, social welfare and pensions, plus improved public sector
efficiency, as very necessary for Germany to boost employment and
ensure continued economic upswing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
