<HEADLINE> Debutant Former National Coach Wins 1st League Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Chinese national coach Qi
Wusheng, who took over as Wuhan Hongjinlong's head coach on
Tuesday, helped the relegation-threatened club score the first win
in 12 matches by beating the Shenyang Haishi 2-0 here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was also the first match Qi has coached in the
professional league. He had been out of coaching any team since
he failed to lead the China to qualify for the France World Cup
finals last November.
</P>
<P>
Cai Sheng opened the scoring in the injury time of the first
half, eluding the Haishi goalie to shoot his seventh goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
With eighth minutes remaining, Li Xiao shook off two defenders
from the left side and arched a long cross, which was headed home
by teammate Ding Lei.
</P>
<P>
The long-waited victory gave the struggling Hongjinlong a big
leap from the bottom of the 14-team standings to climb to the 12th
place. The Wuhan side, which was playing its first season in the
first division league, now holds a win-draw-loss records of 3-6-7
after 16-round competition.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Hainiu was forced to a 1-1 draw in the dying time by
the visiting Shanghai Shenhua. Hainiu went ahead in the 58th
minute by a goal from Cao Xiandong and led the game until
Shenhua's Wu Bing scored the equalizer in the last minute.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other games, Yanbian Aodong stunned Sichuan
Quanxing 2-1, Guangzhou Songri played an goalless draw with
Chinese Army, Beijing Guo'an beat Guangzhou Apollo 1-0, Vanguard
Huandao defeated Shandong Luneng 1-0 and defending champion Dalian
Wanda overpowered Shenzhen Ping'an 4-1. 
</P>
