<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Arrives for Grand Jury Testimony on Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky entered a federal courthouse here on Thursday to
testify on her relationship with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
She was ready to testify to a federal grand jury that she had a
sexual relationship with Clinton, unidentified sources were quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old was whisked into a side entrance of the
courthouse, avoiding a crowd of more than a hundred journalists
who had gathered overnight.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Lewinsky, who had undergone intense preparation
with Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's prosecutors, was ready to
testify truthfully and anxious to finish the painful ordeal.
</P>
<P>
Clinton denied an affair in his testimony in the Paula Jones
civil suit against him. The president will testify to the federal
grand jury on August 17 by closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky was granted blanket immunity from prosecution by Starr
in return for her testimony.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors are investigating whether Clinton committed perjury
in the Jones lawsuit and conspired with Lewinsky and others to
cover up their relationship.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton's mood was "great", White House spokesman
Barry Toiv said Wednesday. "Obviously he is spending some time on
preparing for his testimony," he said. 
</P>
