<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq's Noncompliance "Unacceptable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that Iraq's freezing of cooperation with U.N. weapons
inspectors was "unacceptable" and threatened to keep pressure on
until Iraq complies with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"This noncompliance is completely unacceptable," White House
spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow Iraq access to the resources necessary to
restart their weapons of mass destruction program," he said. "We
will keep the pressure on until Iraq complies fully" with the
U.N.-mandated inspections program.
</P>
<P>
Crowley also said Iraq failed to provide required escorts on
Thursday to a U.N. inspections team seeking to leave its
compound in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the failure to provide the escorts was an indication
that Iraq's threats of noncompliance were being carried out
although there had been no inspection scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"We have evidence on the ground that Iraq is beginning to
follow through on its threats," Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
He said Bill Richardson, U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, had broken off a vacation to attend a U.N. Security
Council briefing by chief weapons inspector Richard Butler on
Thursday.  
</P>
