<HEADLINE> Woman's Body Leaves Haicheng to Return to Taiwan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The body of Lin Ti-chuan, a
Taiwanese woman who was allegedly detained becaused of a business
dispute and later was found dead in northeast China's Liaoning
Province on July 30, was transported today from Haicheng and will
return to Kaohsiung, Taiwan, after making a stopover in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The local public security bureau received a report of Lin's
kidnapping from Wei Tein-kang, Lin's boyfriend who is also a
Taiwan compatriot, on the afternoon of July 29. Jia Chunwang,
minister of Public Security, on the same day ordered the
provincial police department to crack the case as soon as possible.
Zhang Guoguang, governor of Liaoning Province, also made
instructions to the same effect.
</P>
<P>
Lin's body was found in the mortuary of the city's hospital on
the night of July 30. She had been delivered to the hospital for
emergency treatment, according to the hospital's doctors.
</P>
<P>
Liu Gangqi, deputy secretary-general of the Beijing-based
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS),
arrived in Haicheng on July 31, and deputy provincial governor Zhao
Xinliang was sent to the city to take charge of coordinating the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
The city government assigned special personnel to take charge
of the reception work, make reservations for dozens of rooms in
the city's best hotel for Lin's family members and reporters from
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
ARATS quickly arranged for the victim's body to be transported
back to Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman's Body Leaves Haicheng to Return to Taiwan (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Lin's family members and relatives and some Taiwan
reporters arrived in Dalian on the evening of July 31, they did
not have the required documents for entry to the Chinese
mainland. Emergency steps were taken to help them go through the
necessary formalities as soon as possible, and they left Dalian
for Haicheng on the morning of Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland parties concerned did their utmost to meet
the demands of Lin's family members and relatives and offered
greatest possible help, officials said. They allowed a religious
service to be conducted for the dead, though such activities are
banned here, and they set up a mourning hall whose setting
received praise from Taiwan professionals.
</P>
<P>
All applications for reporting the incident from the Taiwanese
side were approved, and nearly 40 Taiwanese journalists gathered
in Haicheng within several days. The city government offered the
reporters convenience, and an official was assigned to provide
help and coordination.
</P>
<P>
"We are shocked and feel sad at the incident, and we hope to
catch the criminals as soon as possible," said a city taxi driver
during an interview with the Taiwan media.
</P>
<P>
A large number of policemen have been mobilized to solve the
crime, and police departments at all levels are focusing on the
case.
</P>
<P>
"We are capable of cracking the case, and it will not take
long," said Liu Gang, director of the city police bureau, while
answering questions raised by Taiwanese reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
