<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman's Body Leaves Haicheng to Return to Taiwan (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A moving donation ceremony was held in the conference hall of
the Haicheng Hotel on the morning of Aug. 2. Local entrepreneurs
and women representatives who were present at the ceremony
expressed their sympathy and solicitude for the family members and
relatives of Lin Ti-chuan. They all condemned the crime and
expressed their hope that the case would not negatively affect
cross-Straits ties.
</P>
<P>
Eight local entrepreneurs donated 85,000 yuan to Lin's father
and expressed the hope that people from both sides of the Taiwan
Straits would be as dear to each other as in the past.
</P>
<P>
Relevant authorities on the mainland made meticulous efforts to
communicate with Lin's family members and to satisfy their demands
while taking into consideration the laws and regulations. They
also clarified some facts about the examination of Lin's remians
and about the Straits Exchange Foundation's demand of sending
representatives to the mainland to help deal with the case.
</P>
<P>
Lin's father time and again gave thanks for the great help
given by concerned departments on the Chinese mainland in dealing
with the death of his daughter.
</P>
<P>
The father's demands for preserving the body of his dead
daughter, holding religious services and transporting the remains
back to Taiwan have all been satisfied since the first day he
arrived in Haicheng, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the autopsy, the father insisted that he would bring
a complete body of his dead daughter back to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to related Chinese laws, examinations must be
performed on victims of criminal cases. The Beijing-based ARATS,
the Liaoning Provincial Taiwan Affairs Office and officials of
Haicheng city invited medical experts from Shenyang, capital city
of Liaoning Province, to minimize the examinations and reduce any
harm to the body.
</P>
</TEXT>
