<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's inflation rate dropped to a record low of 3.6
percent in May, the latest bulletin released by the Central Bank
of Egypt said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund in a report on Egypt's economic
performance attributed the success to hold back the inflation to
Egypt's ongoing trade liberalization and the structural reform,
which increase competition and reduce pressure on prices from
monopolistic practices.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' foreign trade volume reached 465.8 million
Cyrus pounds (about 931.6 million U.S. dollars) in the first
quarter in 1998, an increase of 42.7 million pounds (about 85.4
million dollars) over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The lastest report released Wednesday by the Department of
Statistics and Research with the Finance Ministry showed that
exports amounted to 157.5 million pounds (about 315 million
dollars) in the first quarter of this year from 146.5 million
pounds (about 293 million dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Japan has agreed to grant Jordan 70,000 U.S. dollars
for its water projects in southern Jordan, Jordan's official news
agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The projects aim to ease the water shortage in Tafileh, Ma'an
and Aqaba and make clean water available for the poor in these
areas.
</P>
<P>
The grants are part of a Japanese aid plan for Jordan and Japan
has donated 2.8 million dollars to Jordan so far under the plan.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The European Union (EU) has agreed to provide 42
million U.S. dollars to help modernize Lebanese administrative
system, the Daily star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used for training government staff members
and upgrading office appliances for government departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
