<HEADLINE> Israeli Embassy Aids Chinese Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Embassy today donated 100
sets of tables and chairs to a small primary school in Yanqing
county in the outskirt of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Israel's ambassador to China Ora Namir and other embassy
officials attended today's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
There are 103 students in the school with three teachers.
</P>
<P>
Namir first visited the school in a mountainous area last March
and provided a TV set, a video recorder and a radio for the
students here.
</P>
<P>
Namir said she was happy to meet those "beautiful and
wonderful" students again, and that the embassy will continue
efforts to improve the condition of the school.
</P>
<P>
The event, organized by the All-China Women's Federation, can
be seen as new contribution to China's Spring Bud Project,
according to an official from the Women's Federation.
</P>
<P>
The ten-year-old Spring Bud Project is designed to finance girl
dropouts to return to school. More than 600,000 girl students have
benefited from the project.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli donation will help and encourage students to do a
good job, according to the head of the school.  
</P>
</TEXT>
