<HEADLINE> Mainland Protects Taiwan Compatriots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese official on
cross-Straits affairs reiterated today that mainland authorities
have always exhibited concern and consistently worked to the
legitimate rights and interests of Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yunlin, director of the Taiwan Affairs offices for both
the Communist Party of China Central Committee and the State
Council, made the remark during a banquet held for delegates
attending the seventh Seminar on Relations Across the Taiwan
Straits.
</P>
<P>
"Solutions to problems resulting from contacts between people
across the Straits center on protecting the rights of Taiwan
compatriots, and finding solutions for political differences
concerning their fundamental rights," according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
Wide-ranging contacts, including economic and cultural
exchanges, between people across the Taiwan Straits have increased
in recent years thanks to the joint efforts of people on both
sides, said Chen. However, criminal activities which have
increased along with contacts have endangered both the well-being
and property of people on both sides of the straits.
</P>
<P>
He lamented the recent death of Lin Ti-chuan, a Taiwan woman
who was allegedly kidnaped and consequently died of as yet
undetermined causes, and vowed to apprehend and severely punish the
perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
Chen warned against any attempts to use the case to create
disputes between the two sides of the Straits and hinder the
development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated both the mainland's stand of holding political
talks between the two sides at the earliest possible date and the
invitation for Koo Chen-fu, chairman of Taiwan's Straits Exchange
Foundation to visit to China between mid-September and mid-October
this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
