<HEADLINE> British Foreign Office Denies Claims of Gaddafi Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The British Foreign Office on
Thursday categorically denied claims that British agents attempted
to assassinate Libyan leader Colonel Muammar Gaddafi two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The claims were made by a former member of Britain's security
services MI6, David Shayler, who was arrested in Paris last
weekend and is fighting moves to extradite him back to Britain.
</P>
<P>
"The central claim that there was an official plot to kill
Gaddafi is untrue," a Foreign Office spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"It is inconceivable in normal peacetime circumstances that
authority for the secret intelligence services to conduct
assassination attempts would be granted," he added.
</P>
<P>
The claims were reported in Thursday's Guardian newspaper after
appearing first in the New York Times on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Guardian, Shayler allegedly said that
Britain's foreign intelligence service MI6 tried to kill Gaddafi
in February 1996 by planting a bomb under his motorcade. But, he
said, agents placed the bomb under the wrong car, killing several
bystanders.
</P>
<P>
Britain has traditionally revealed little about the work of MI5
and its partner agency, MI6, which gathers intelligence abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
