<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Leaves Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England's Monetary
Policy Committee decided on Thursday to keep interest rates
unchanged at 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Many experts had predicted the rate would remain unmoved in
view of the gloomy outlook for the British economy.
</P>
<P>
The decision came as a relief to home owners and businesses,
but it will spark fresh demands for the committee to cut rates.
</P>
<P>
Ian Peters, deputy director general of the British Chambers
of Commerce, warmly welcomed the decision, saying: "This decision
plainly reflects the now abundant 'real world' evidence that the
economy is slowing sufficiently."
</P>
<P>
But he said the manufacturing industry "remains dangerously
close to the brink and job losses and company closures will
continue".
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that in September the Monetary Policy Committee
must cut rates by 0.25 percent."
</P>
<P>
Financial markets had expected no change after a monthly
rate-setting meeting and although Sterling dipped on the news, it
soon recovered.
</P>
<P>
Already weak shares barely budged and British government bonds
soon lost the modest gains made on the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates have risen six times since the election in May
of last year, from six percent to 7.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
