<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Otto Unlikely to Worsen Flooding on Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese meteorologists today
predict that Typhoon Otto which hit China's coast Wednesday will
not intensify flooding on the Yangtze river, the worst since 1954.
</P>
<P>
Landing at Fuqing City in east China's Fujian province
yesterday morning with a maximum force of eight, Typhoon Otto has
quickly subsided by force less than six as it moved northwest,
bringing heavy rain and rainstorms to most of Fujian and the
southeast of neighboring Jiangxi province, according to China
Central Meteorological Station.
</P>
<P>
Having subsided to low pressure, meteorologists said that
Typhoon Otto will not cause strong winds and rains in China over
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The experts pointed out that typhoon activities this year have
showed a queer pattern, with only two formed as late as August 5,
and predicted that five to seven typhoons will land in China
within the next three months.
</P>
<P>
China has an area of about 290,000 square kilometers affected
by typhoons each year, mainly in the more developed coastal
region. Experts warn provinces to closely follow the typhoon to
prepare for emergencies and protect people's lives and properties.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that eleven coastal provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions have invested close to one
billion yuan in consolidating 611 reservoirs and 1,733 kilometers of
levees. Up to now 226 counties and cities, or about 70 percent of
the total in the coastal region, have established systems
receiving satellite cloud maps.
</P>
<P>
The coastal region has also increased their supplies of flood
control materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
