<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Helps Redirect Talents of CIS Military Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Science and Technology
Centers set up by the European Union and other countries are
redirecting the talents of former Soviet Union military scientists
to peaceful projects.
</P>
<P>
Lousewies van der Laan, representing the European Commission's
external relations commissioner Hans van den Broek, said on
Thursday that the science and technology centers in Moscow and
Kiev will help Russian and Ukrainian military scientists to lend
their know-how to new ends.
</P>
<P>
The scientists included nuclear, biological and chemical
weaponry experts who had been associated with the research and
development of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European Union also expects to integrate the
talents of Russian and Ukrainian military scientists into the
international scientific community.
</P>
<P>
Since its start in March 1994, the International Science and
Technology Center in Moscow has approved more than 590 projects
with a value of nearly 160 million ECUs (176 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The funds provide support to some 20,000 scientists and
engineers in the Russian Federation and in Armenia, Belarus,
Georgia, Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow center was set up in line with an international
agreement between the European Union, the United States, Japan and
the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
The Kiev center in Ukraine has, since its inauguration in 1995,
endorsed 133 projects with 17 million ECUs (18.7 million dollars)
of funds which are used to support 2,300 scientists and engineers.
</P>
<P>
The Kiev center was established according to agreements between
the United States, Canada and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has so far provided 62 million ECUs (68.2
million dollars) of funds for 302 of the Moscow center's projects
and three million ECUs (3.3 million dollars) to the Kiev
center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
