<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Government Gets Tough on Rail Blockades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Boris Nemtsov said Thursday that state funding will be cut to the
coal industry in regions where striking miners are blocking
railways.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not accept any demands of striking miners
accompanied by railway blockades," Nemtsov told reporters in the
Government House.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that financing would be resumed only after the
re-introduction of public order, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came at a time when many railways are blocked
around the country by striking miners demanding the payment of
back wages.
</P>
<P>
In the Far Eastern region of Sakhalin, a 12-day railway
stoppage pushed the island to the brink of a black-out as the
power station was running out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
As a result, local citizens have endured power cuts of up to
14 hours a day. Sakhalin is not connected to Russia's national
power grid, leaving most of the island's 650,000 residents
dependent on the plant for electricity.
</P>
<P>
A more worrying threat came from the southern Urals region of
Chelyabinsk where coal miners have blocked access to the
Argayashkaya power plant that supplies heat and electricity to
Mayak, Russia's only nuclear waste processing plant.
</P>
<P>
Workers of the civil defense service have been dispatched to
the site amid fears that electronic safety systems might break
down.
</P>
<P>
Miners across Russia rocked the government in May when they
blocked key railway lines such as the Trans-Siberian in a protest
that cost the Railways Ministry an estimated 355 million rubles
(57 million U.S. dollars) in lost freight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
