<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Memoirs of Lee Kuan Yew" Due to Be Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Three well-known publishing
groups announced here Thursday that they have agreed to jointly
publish the memoirs of Singapore's Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew
who himself put his life experience into words.
</P>
<P>
The publishing groups are the Publishing Singapore Press
Holdings (SPH) and Times, that will publish the book for the
Singapore and Malaysian markets, and the Simon &AMP; Schuster Asia,
which will publish the book for the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
A news release from the SPH said, "From 1995, it took Mr. Lee
three years to put into words his 75 years of life experience,
especially his political experience in the last 45 years to
produce the memoirs of more than one million words."
</P>
<P>
The news release said, "The memoirs, which will come in two
separate volumes, the first dealing with the author's early years
up to Singapore Independence and the second with his life from
then to the present day, provides a vivid account of the making of
Singapore as well as a fascinating insight into the man who
transformed Singapore and shape its history."
</P>
<P>
Simon &AMP; Schuster Asia Publishing Director Stephen Troth said,
"This is an important book for us written by one of the region's
foremost political thinkers. During this time of political and
economic upheaval in Asia, we feel a reflective book of this sort
will be of great interest. The author's views are already well
known and respected in Asia but we feel that they will also be of
interest to wider audience outside."
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the first volume, titled "The
Singapore Story: Memoirs of Lee Kuan Yew", will be published to
coincide with the author's 75th birthday on September 16.
</P>
<P>
The Memoirs will be published both in English and Chinese. The
First volume of the Chinese version, which was translated by a
team of Lianhe Zaobao journalists and writers who worked closely
with Lee to carry out the translation and editing work
simultaneously, will come out at the same time with the English
version.
</P>
<P>
The SPH news release said, "In it, Mr. Lee gives a vivid
description and recollection of his years of growing up, political
struggles, and experience in nation building."
</P>
<P>
"There are many interesting inside stories and invaluable
historical facts which he is making known for the first time," it
added.
</P>
<P>
It also said that "the second volume is scheduled to be
published next year. Here Mr. Lee would discuss the
post-independence days, the problems he encountered in developing
the society, education, defense, economy and infrastructure and
how he came up with various policies to overcome them."
</P>
<P>
"He would also dwell on how he opened up Singapore to forge
ties with its neighbors and the world in the last 40 years and
what he has learnt from the success and failure of other
countries," it added.
</P>
<P>
Lee Kuan Yew, born in 1923, became Singapore's first prime
minister in 1959 when Singapore achieved self-government and he
was 35 years of age. He continued to be the prime minister after
the country's independence and served on for 31 years before he
left the post in 1990 to become senior minister of the Cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
