<HEADLINE> South African Top Officials to Meet Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A three-man South African
ministerial delegation headed by Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo will
travel to the Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R.Congo) Friday
morning for talks with embattled President Laurent Kabila in his
Lubumbashi stronghold.
</P>
<P>
"We're not carrying solutions... we're interested in getting
the view of the government. If they need us to do anything, we'll
discuss it," South African Press Association Thursday quoted Nzo
as saying in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
He would be accompanied by Defense Minister Joe Modise and
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi.
</P>
<P>
The one-day visit follows talks earlier this week between
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and Kabila, after
uprisings in the country against his rule.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters whether he would also be willing at some
stage to meet the rebels, headed by veteran politician Arthur
Zahidi Ngoma, Nzo said: "We will be very ready to meet anybody to
have that situation resolved."
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation in the D.R.Congo as "critical", Nzo
said the South African delegation would be very happy to receive
a briefing from Kabila on the developments in his country.
</P>
<P>
Replying on whether outside military intervention might be
necessary, Nzo said: "Why are you so war-like? We are a peaceful
people, we are for a diplomatic solution all the time."
</P>
<P>
Banyamulenge soldiers who helped Kabila to oust Mobutu Sese
Seko last year rebelled against Kabila last Sunday after they
were ordered to go home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
