<HEADLINE> EUYO Musicians to Tour EU Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Music-lovers in seven European
Union member countries will soon be able to enjoy concerts by
Europe's best young musicians.
</P>
<P>
The European Union announced Thursday that later this month and
early in September, 140 musicians aged between 14 and 23 will give
concerts in Sweden, Finland, Austria, Germany, Portugal, Spain and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The touring musicians were chosen from over 4,000 candidates.
</P>
<P>
A new European Union Young Orchestra (EUYO) is selected every
year, and members of the previous year's EUYO orchestra have to be
auditioned again before being selected.
</P>
<P>
The orchestra will stop in Stockholm, Gavle, Helsinki, Hamina,
Vienna, Graz, Dusseldorf, Lisbon, Santander and London between
August 22 and September 5.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Ashkenazy is to conduct the EUYO orchestra for the
ninth time.
</P>
<P>
The concerts are a varied and exciting display of orchestral
works by classic and modern composers, including the 1998
Masterprize winner Andrew March's "Marine a travers les arbres".
</P>
<P>
The EUYO was formed in 1976 by the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
World-famous conductors who have worked with the orchestra
include Antal Dorati, Daniel Barenboim, Leonard Bernstein, Sir
Colin Davis, Carlo Maria Giulini, Herbert von Karajan, Zubin
Mehta, Mstislav Rostropovich and Sir Georg Solti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
