<HEADLINE> Mandela to Rally Neighbors on Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela was trying to rally neighboring heads of state to
deal with disturbing developments in Lesotho following its May
general election, Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The South African government had already been in contact with
Zimbabwe and Botswana on Lesotho, South African Press Association
quoted Nzo as saying at a media briefing.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Lesotho riot police were deployed at the Lesotho
parliament in Maseru to maintain law and order as crowds of
opposition protesters gathered outside the parliament gate.
</P>
<P>
The gathering prevented both houses of parliament to meet at
the scheduled time.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, all supporters of the three main opposition
parties - the Basotholand Congress Party, the Basotho National
Party and the Marematlou Freedom Party - were protesting against
the outcome of the May 29 general election.
</P>
<P>
They said the polls were rigged and the results, a landslide
victory for the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD),
should be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
The angry mob, armed with heavy sticks, shouted
anti-government slogans and sang battle songs. Some stood face to
face with riot police fully armed with riot gear, batons, shields
and tear gas equipment.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and his
cabinet were held hostage inside parliament by the protesters for
an hour after Mosisili addressed parliament on the present
political situation in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The three main opposition parties staged a march Tuesday to
present a petition to King Letsie III, asking him to intervene in
the matter. 
</P>
