<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Switching To Low-Sulphur Coal To Reduce Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is planning on reducing
sulphur and smoke emissions by keeping coal that fails to meet
low-sulphur criteria off the market, according to Vice-Mayor Liu
Haiyan.
</P>
<P>
Liu told a meeting of 200 officials in charge of coal
purchasing today that this is Beijing's first ruling of its
kind. It says that coal used for heating in winter can contain no
more than 5 parts sulphur per thousand.
</P>
<P>
Like most of Chinese cities, Beijing relies on coal for its
main energy source and burns 27 million tons of it each year, with
5 million tons of that for heating purposes from November to March.
</P>
<P>
Yu Xiaoxuan, deputy director of the Beijing Environmental
Protection Bureau, said that the amount of sulphur dioxide in the
air was higher than state limits three times and caused
respiratory problems for many residents.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is now one of the most seriously polluted cities in
China. Its main pollutants are smoke from coal, motor vehicle
exhaust emissions, and dust from various sources.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting of officials it was pointed out that the use of
low-sulphur coal will reduce sulphur dioxide and soot emissions by
about 70,000 tons each in the wintertime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0093 </DOCNO>
