<HEADLINE> Indonesian Armed Forces to Protect Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Armed Forces
(ABRI) will take concrete measures to protect national economic
activities from criminal acts like looting and theft, ABRI Chief
Gen. Wiranto said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI will address security problems that disturb the
government's efforts to improve the economy," Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
After attending a limited coordination meeting on economic,
financial and industrial affairs here, Wiranto said criminal acts
in the economic field had increased in frequency lately and ABRI
therefore needed to step up its efforts to fight them.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Yunus Yosfiah told reporters that the
criminal acts might well have been masterminded by certain
quarters.
</P>
<P>
To find out who were behind the criminal acts, including the
looting that occurred in different parts of the country recently,
intelligence operations had to be carried out, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yosfiah said that Forestry and Plantations Minister Muslimin
Nasution had reported that lawless acts such as looting had also
occurred in the forestry sector.
</P>
<P>
One state-owned forestry company in East Java province had lost
13,600 teak trees due to theft or looting.
</P>
<P>
Instances of forest tree theft also happened in South
Banyuwangi, Probolinggo and Jatirogo, all in East Java province.
</P>
</TEXT>
