<HEADLINE> Indian Parliament Ends Budget Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The two-month-long budget
session of the Indian parliament concluded Thursday with sine die
adjournment of the Lower House after transacting important
financial legislative and other business.
</P>
<P>
The Upper House of the Parliament, Rajya Sabha, was adjourned
sine die Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During 38 sittings spanning about 280 hours, the Lower House,
Lok Sabha, passed the general budget, the railway budget along
with 22 bills.
</P>
<P>
The controversial Women's Reservation Bill could not be
introduced in the House due to stiff resistance by some parties
while the bill on creation of separate states of Uttaranchal,
Vananchal and Chhattisgarn and granting of statehood to Delhi were
deferred.
</P>
<P>
The session saw heated debates over India's nuclear tests in
May, the final report of the so-called Jain Commission of Inquiry
on the assassination of former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi in 1989
and foreign policy under the government led by Bharatiya Janata
Party.
</P>
<P>
The Lok Sabha also discussed, among others, the insurgency in
the Northeast, situation in Jammu and Kashmir, flood situation in
the states of Assam and Bihar, price rise and incidents of suicide
by farmers.
</P>
<P>
The House passed 22 bills including setting up of the
Electricity Regulatory Commission, salary increase for high court
and supreme court judges, the president and vice president, and
governors and members of Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
