<HEADLINE> Rights of Ethnic Chinese in Indonesia Should Be Respected: Wu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China has urged the Indonesian
government to protect the rights and interests of ethnic Chinese
in Indonesia after they were targeted by rioters in May.
</P>
<P>
China was deeply concerned about the plight of the ethnic
Chinese and was urging the Indonesian government to punish the
culprits severely, said a Chinese diplomat Thursday at a
United Nations Meeting here on human rights.
</P>
<P>
Repeated representations had been made to the Indonesian
government through diplomatic channels to that effect, said
Wu Jianmin, Permanent Representative of the Permanent Mission of
the People's Republic of China to the United Nations office in
Geneva and to other International Organizations in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government had asked the Indonesian government to
"take effective measures to safeguard the personal safety and
legitimate rights and interests of ethnic Chinese in Indonesia,
and prevent the occurrence of similar incidents", said the
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
During the riots which took place in some cities in Indonesia
in May, many shops owned by ethnic Chinese were ransacked and
burned and many ethnic Chinese women were savagely raped.
</P>
<P>
The atrocities have sparked grave concern and indignation of
the Chinese people and Chinese associations abroad, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
"We have noticed that Indonesian President B.J. Habibie labeled
it 'the most inhuman event in the history of the nation' and
ordered a special investigation committee to be set up," Wu said
at the sub-commission on the prevention of discrimination and
protection of minorities of the UN Human Rights Committee.
</P>
<P>
Wu noted that the Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas also
called the incidents "the shame of Indonesia". 
</P>
</TEXT>
