<HEADLINE> France Urges Iraq to Resume Cooperation with UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- France Thursday urged Iraq to
resume cooperation with both the United Nations Special Commission
on disarmament in Iraq (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA).
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry described Wednesday's decision by
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM
and the IAEA as "unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
"France recalls its attachment to the letter and spirit of the
agreement of February 23, 1998, between the United Nations and
Iraq," said a Foreign Ministry statement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz in Baghdad, averted an air
strike by the United States and Britain on suspected chemical and
biological weapons targets in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
France had greatly contributed to the signing of this agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The special commission and the IAEA which have completed a
better part of the disarmament program of Iraq should be in the
place to achieve their mission, in the perspective of a lifting of
the sanctions and the full re-integration of Iraq in the
international community," said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi decision to freeze cooperation with UNSCOM and the
IAEA was made after the latest round of talks between UNSCOM
Chairman Richard Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
broke down Monday night. 
</P>
