<HEADLINE> EU Grants Humanitarian Aid for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Thursday granted humanitarian aid worth five million ECUs (5.5
million U.S. dollars) for victims of the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The aid, to be managed by the European Community Humanitarian
Office, will enable the United Nations and non-governmental
organizations to carry out emergency programs for those fleeing
the fighting in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The priorities for aid agencies are food, health care,
sanitation, shelter and materials needed by those affected by
wintry weather.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said the conflict in Kosovo had escalated
dramatically in the summer months, and the number of displaced
people fleeing to Albania is now estimated at 13,000, with 27,000
taking refuge in Montenegro and 2,000 in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
The number of displaced people still in Kosovo was estimated at
well over 100,000.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of the displaced are women and children.
</P>
<P>
The European Community Humanitarian Office has previously
offered aid worth 1.5 million ECUs (1.65 million dollars) for
those affected by the Kosovo crisis. The aid focused on assisting
refugees who fled to Albania. 
</P>
