<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Opposition Parties Fail to Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Talks between South
Africa's various opposition parties have failed to bring about
unity, and the parties will each go it alone in next year's
general election,
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP) and the Democratic Party (DP) are set
on a collision course, with each determined to be the official
opposition in the new parliament, and neither able to guess at
the strength of the United Democratic Movement (UDM), The Citizen
daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We sent the Nats (National Party) our set of proposals, and
there was a stony silence," DP leader Tony Leon said at day-long
briefings by opposition leaders to ambassadors and journalists at
parliament in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Leon said there was still possible cooperation with others to
ensure that opposition groups were equitably treated in the
election process, including coverage on television.
</P>
<P>
It was also possible that in some provinces there would be a
need for cooperation between parties after the election.
</P>
<P>
"Beyond that, the Democratic Party will certainly fight the
election under its own colors," said Leon.
</P>
<P>
The NP had been the official opposition since 1994, but recent
opinion polls showed that it was losing support. With only a year
to go before the 1999 elections it was unlikely that the NP would
turn the tide of unfavorable public opinion.
</P>
<P>
"The trend away from the NP in recent by-elections is so
pronounced that the party is likely to lose its status as the
official opposition in 1999. The DP is in a position to become
the official opposition," said Leon.
</P>
<P>
Leon said he believed the UDM was unlikely to gain much
support outside the Eastern Cape province.
</P>
<P>
The naming of former warlord Sifiso Nkabinde as the UDM's
general secretary would harm it at the poll, he said.
</P>
<P>
NP leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk described contact between
the parties, aimed at possible election cooperation, as
"disappointing".
</P>
<P>
However, the NP was determined to retain control of the
Western Cape and win the Northern Cape in next year's election.
The national goal was to prevent a two-thirds majority for the
ruling African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
Van Schalkwyk believed that no party would be able to garner
50 percent of the votes in KwaZulu-Natal, making a post-election
coalition almost certain.
</P>
<P>
He said the NP was still in favor of some kind of cooperation
between like-minded parties, but the kind of cooperation it
wanted did not seem to be attainable.
</P>
<P>
"It will be difficult to do it before the election, but I have
always said we can do it after the election," van Schalkwyk said.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front leader Constand Viljoen said he was also in
favor of cooperation between different opposition parties in an
effort to prevent a two-thirds majority for the ANC.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that in the proportional voting system it is
possible to cooperate with other parties in achieving this,
without losing your identity as a political party or being forced
to use one candidate's list," said Viljoen.
</P>
<P>
Pan Africanist Congress (PAC) leader Stanley Mogoba said the
PAC had built up a presence in all nine provinces with
"phenomenal" growth in North-West, Northern Province, Eastern
Cape, Gauteng and Free State.
</P>
<P>
"Our experience throughout is that our policy enjoys wide
acceptance," Mogoba said.
</P>
<P>
African Christian Democratic Party leader Kenneth Meshoe, who
heads the smallest of the opposition parties in parliament, also
forecast gains for his party in the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
