<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Price Slump Hits North Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The price slump of Burley tobacco
on the international markets has hit the major planter, the
northern Nampula Province of Mozambique, according to the local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The provincial bureau of agriculture and fishery disclosed
recently that one kilogram of Class A Burley tobacco, which could
be sold for 13,000 Metical (12,000 Metical equals one U.S.
Dollar) last year, is sold for only 12,000 Metical now.
</P>
<P>
The officials pointed out that the falling purchase prices of
the tobacco has angered the farmers who said that it is unfair
for them to suffer the loss.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco prices for the classes of B and C per kilogram
also decreased by 1,000 Metical each. One kilogram of Class D
Burley tobacco is now sold for 6,000 Metical while the price for
last year was 8,000 Metical.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some tobacco farmers often manage to
smuggle their produce to the neighboring countries for better
prices.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 500 tons of tobacco leaf was smuggled
from the provinces of Niassa and Zambezia to Malawi, causing a
loss of eight billion Metical to Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The experts predicted that Nampula Province is expected to
harvest 796 tons of tobacco leaf in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Denies Arrests Linked to Settlers Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) denied Thursday that the recent arrests by
Palestinian police in the West Bank were linked to the killing of
two Jewish settlers, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted an unnamed senior PNA official as saying that
the arrests made in the Palestinian villages near the West Bank
town of Nablus had nothing to do with the shooting of two Jewish
settlers late Tuesday night in Itzhar, a settlement near Nablus.
</P>
<P>
He said the arrests were carried out only as general
preventative security measures.
</P>
<P>
In earlier reports, the radio said Palestinian police had
aided the Israeli army in a search for the killers, arresting
several residents of Nablus Wednesday night as suspects.
</P>
<P>
Israel has expressed its dissatisfaction over the lack of a
public denouncement from PNA President Yasser Arafat of the
killing.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat's adviser Ahmed Tibi explained that although the PNA
deplores such violence, it distinguishes between Israeli citizens
and settlers at Itzhar and other settlements, who are opposed to
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Tibi charged the settlers for working against the
self-determination by the Palestinian people, saying there was no
point for any comment from Arafat over the attack incident.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, during a condolence visit to the families of the
two slain settlers, Israeli President Ezer Weizman expressed
support for the continuation of the peace talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But the outspoken president, who has been pressing hard-line
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to continue the peace process,
was also dissatisfied with the Palestinian response to the
killing, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the shooting incident, Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators are reportedly to resume contacts later Thursday to
set up another negotiating session in a continued effort to clinch
a deal on the overdue Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has said that he thought an agreement on the second
pullback could be reached shortly, but Tuesday's attack
underscored the need to make security arrangment in any deal with
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
