group of Al-Itihad Al-Islam and the Somali National Front (SNF)
faction of General Omar Haji Masalle have reached a peace deal
after a 20-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two sides Wednesday concluded the final six-point deal in
the El-Adde village of the border region Gedo.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two sides, Ali Mohamed Mukhtar (deputy
chairman of the SNF faction) and Sheikh Mohamud Moallim Nur
(deputy chairman of Al-Itihad), told reporters via VHF radio in
Mogadishu Wednesday that this agreement is historic and decisive.
</P>
<P>
The agreed points include the cessation of hostilities, paving
the way for co-existence and the creation of a peaceful
environment for demining all roads for the commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
Each of the two sides had earlier mined all roads leading to
the strongholds of the opposite side as part of an easy defensive
tactic used throughout Somalia since the breakout of the civil
war in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The deal also includes the use of SNF as the political emblem
for the region and the reimposition of the Islamic Sharia laws.
</P>
<P>
Another important item in the agreement is that the peaceful
co-existence with the neighboring countries and that a high-level
mission be sent to these countries.
</P>
<P>
This would mean particularly the end of hostilities with
Ethiopia. Al-Itihad Al-Islam had long been accused of
instigating bombing raids in many parts inside Ethiopia,
including the capital city of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
In an alleged pursuit of Al-Itihad, the Ethiopian forces had
crossed into Somalia in two large military incursions in Gedo
region in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also called for the restructuring of SNF with
Al-Itihad in another meeting to be held in the capital of the
region, Garbaharrey.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal between SNF and Al-Itihad Al-Islam can be
characterized as a positive step forward, considering the peace
process throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, a controversial administration had been
announced in the northeastern regions while another similar one
was announced here in Mogadishu four days ago.
</P>
<P>
All these movements show tentative peace-making efforts after
almost eight years of anarchy in Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
