<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Expands National Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has expanded the
Katavi National Park in the western region of Rukwa to provide
more areas for wild animals there.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the extended park on Wednesday, President
Benjamin Mkapa said the wildlife should be protected not only for
the benefit of Tanzania but for the whole world.
</P>
<P>
The German government has granted over four billion Shillings
(about 5.97 million U.S. Dollars) for Katavi Park expansion while
Tanzania has raised 27.4 million Shillings for it, the Daily News
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The park, one of the 12 national parks in the east African
country, was first set up by the government in 1974 with an area
of 2,253 square kilometers. It has been expanded to 4,471 square
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The park, characterized by Miombo Woodland and water-logged
plains, is famous for Sable and Roan antelopes which are rarely
found in other parks in the country. It also has a high
population density of crocodiles, water bucks, hartbeest and
Greater Kudu among other large mammals.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Tanzanian National Parks (TANAPA) acting
Director-General said the expansion of the park will provide a
larger area, including mountains in the north, for the migration
of animals.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa also appealed to the international donors to
complement the Tanzanian government's efforts in wildlife
conservation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
