<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea's Foreign Debts Down to 153.8 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign debt fell to
153.8 billion U.S. dollars at the end of June, down 1.2 billion
dollars from a month earlier, the Ministry of Finance and Economy
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In June, long-term liabilities rose 900 million dollars
due to the inflow of funds from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) while short-term ones fell 2.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of short-term debts declined from 26.1 percent
in May to 24.9 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
However, debts which should be repaid by the public sector
expanded to 30.7 billion U.S. dollars late in the month.
</P>
<P>
Domestic financial institutions' short-term debts dropped by
1.3 billion dollars to 69.6 billion in June from May while the
long-term ones fell by 100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the private sector's external debts edged down 100
million to 37.8 billion dollars in June despite a fresh commercial
loan of 260 million.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the nation's foreign debt grew
by 12.6 billion dollars in the public sector, but declined 5.6
billion and 4.4 billion respectively in financial and private
business sectors.
</P>
<P>
South Korea borrowed 58 billion dollars from the IMF last
December after it was gripped by a financial crisis caused by
corporate failures and bad loans of financial institutions late
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
