<HEADLINE> Second Minister Resigns From Arafat's Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- In a sign indicating the
growing discontent with failure to tackle corruption within the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), a second minister in the new
PNA cabinet announced resignation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Jawad Saleh, a newly appointed minister without portfolio
in the PNA cabinet, announced his decision at a news conference in
the West Bank city Ramallah to follow up the step of Minister of
Tourism and Archaeology Hanan Ashrawi.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi announced her resignation at an earlier news conference
in Ramallah in protest against the lack of comprehensive reform in
the cabinet reshuffle made by PNA President Yasser Arafat on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the new lineup of the cabinet, all ministers
accused of being corrupt in the previous cabinet retained their
jobs despite that it was the accusation of corruption and
inefficiency that led to the latest cabinet shakeup by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said he was not satisfied with the cabinet reshuffle
announced by Arafat on Wednesday and decided to leave the new
government.
</P>
<P>
Saleh, an independent member of the Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) elected from Biret, near Ramallah, was minister of
agriculture in the former cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Arafat presented Wednesday his new cabinet to the PLC which has
decided to vote on the reshuffle on Saturday. 
</P>
