<HEADLINE> Wariso Cleared to Run at Commonwealth Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- British runner Solomon Wariso has
been cleared to take part in the Commonwealth Games in Kuala
Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old 400m runner was originally banned for life from
the Games after he was tested positive for an illegal stimulant in
1994. He was suspended for three months for taking an ephedrine
derivative in a product called Up Your Gas.
</P>
<P>
But the chairman of the Commonwealth Games panel, Jeff
Cook,said Wariso had now been cleared to compete for England.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting on Wednesday the appeal panel ruled that it was"a
minor breach caused by a genuine mistake for which Wariso has
served his penalty."
</P>
<P>
"Solomon is genuinely sorry for what happened and believes it
was a genuine mistake and is now clear on our account to run in
the Commonwealth Games," Cook said. 
