<HEADLINE> Exam Results Sent to HK Form Five Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Test slips will be handed
Thursday to more than 134,000 local Secondary Five (Form Five)
graduates who sat for the Hong Kong Certificate for Education
Examination (HKCEC).
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong Examinations Authority, improvements
were shown in the overall performance of the students this year.
</P>
<P>
The authority said 62.4 percent of them got a pass in all
subjects taken, a mere 0.6 percentage points higher than last
year's 61.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
While there are about 24,200 Secondary Six places available,
only 20,729 candidates, or 23.8 percent, achieved 14 points or
more in their best six subjects, the minimum entry requirement to
Secondary Six places.
</P>
<P>
Result slips, showing the points students received in the best
six papers, will be distributed to school candidates Thursday
through their schools or mailed to private candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department of the Special Administrative Region has
opened two counseling centers, answering inquiries about school
application and job hunting while volunteer organizations set up
more than 100 hotlines to serve the students.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa on Wednesday evening offered
encouraging words to those who had attained less satisfactory
results in the exam.
</P>
<P>
"I hope you will not be despondent. Failure is the only high
road to success. To fail once does not mean that this is the end
of everything," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive also congratulated those who had attained
good results and advised them not to be complacent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
