<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Rejects Greek Definition of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada said here
Thursday that a newly released Greek-English dictionary's
inaccurate definition of a Filipina as a housemaid is "totally
unacceptable" and an affront to the dignity of Filipino women.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to point out that this definition is severely
inaccurate and lacking in academic research. As much as it is
offensive, its negative connotation downgrades the positive
contribution of Filipino women to the economic and social
development of the Philippines and of Greece," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada stressed that the error should be corrected as soon as
possible "in view of the cordial relations between the Philippines
and Greece."
</P>
<P>
The dictionary was authored by a certain George Babiniotis.
</P>
<P>
The president said Filipino women have distinguished themselves
not only at home but also in the international community.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Filipinas have occupied not only high
positions in Congress but the presidency of the Philippines as
well, adding they have also been recognized as leaders in the
academics and business.
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore an affront to the dignity and person of the
Filipino woman to confine her description within the limited
definition of a domestic helper. Mr. Babiniotis' definition is
totally unacceptable and not based on fact," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada asked the Greek government to call Babiniotis'
attention to the serious error so that the author could
immediately make necessary correction.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Ambassador to Greece Norberto Basilio earlier filed
an official protest before the Greek government questioning the
inaccurate definition.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has at least 6.5 million contract workers in
more than 100 countries and regions around the world. Most of the
workers are female. 
</P>
</TEXT>
