<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Militant Attacks Decline in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Attacks by Islamic militants in
Egypt have sharply decreased in the first seven months of this
year as a result of tough crackdown by the police, the Al Ahram
weekly reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language edition quoted security sources as saying
that the security forces have reduced the operations of the
militants by 85 percent in southern Egypt and completely cut off
their sources of financing and armament.
</P>
<P>
The number of victims killed in terrorist acts has also dropped
significantly, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nine civilians and six policemen were killed in the first
seven months of 1998 compared with 50 civilians and 44 policemen
in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The sources attributed the decline to a multi-prong security
strategy worked out by the Interior Ministry after the Luxor
massacrer last November, in which 58 foreign tourists were killed.
</P>
<P>
Security forces have since launched raids against militants'
hide-outs in southern provinces of Minya, Assuit and Qena, killing
16 militants.
</P>
<P>
As part of the new strategy, the police force is changing its
infamous and often boomerang heavy-handedness, which has led to
haphazard arrests and massive sentences.
</P>
<P>
During the past seven months, 2,500 people, who were detained
without charge on suspicion of links with Islamic militant groups
and proven innocent, have been released.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry is continuing the policy of organizing
discussions between Islamic scholars and detainees with the aim of
"correcting their misconceptions."
</P>
<P>
Nearly 5,000 detainees have repented after the correction
sessions and decided to renounce the ideology of Al Gamaa Al
Islamiya, Egypt's largest Islamic militant group.
</P>
<P>
Anti-government Islamic militants have been fighting to
overthrow the secular government led by President Hosni Mubarak in
order to establish an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
The armed militants often target foreign tourists in an attempt
to hurt the country's tourism, the leading earner of foreign
exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
