<HEADLINE> Consultancy Agreement signed for West African Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A consultancy agreement for the
feasibility study on the West African Gas Pipeline Project has
been signed between Pipeline Engineering of Germany and a
consortium of four multi-national companies.
</P>
<P>
The Punch newspaper reported Thursday that the study would be
ready in the first quarter of 1999 at a cost of two million U.S.
Dollars and would entail technical and commercial analysis of the
conditions required to implement the project.
</P>
<P>
The consortium comprises Chevron Nigeria Ltd., Nigeria Gas
Company (NGC), Shell Petroleum Development Company, Ghana
National Petroleum Corporation and Societe Beniniose de Gaz S.A..
</P>
<P>
NGC General Manager Jackson Gaius-Obaseki was quoted as saying
Wednesday that through the gas pipeline project, the abundant
resources of natural gas in Nigeria can be used to satisfy the
energy requirements of the sub-region of west Africa.
</P>
<P>
The concept of the West African Gas Pipeline Project was
predicated on the need to meet the energy requirements of the
sub-region through the transmission of natural gas from Nigeria
to Benin, Togo and Ghana for power generation and other uses, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The idea of a sub-regional gas pipeline was first
conceptualized when the petroleum and energy ministers of the
four countries signed an agreement on the proposed project in
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, a group of four companies including
U!Yd=91+ R-Xna National Petroleum Corporation and the
Nigerian Gas Company inaugurated a private sector initiative in
order to accelerate the project implementation through a joint
preparation of a detailed, feasibility study.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has abundant natural gas resources which is estimated
at between 15 trillion and 30 trillion cubic feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
