<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt. Not Overborrowing: Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) --Zimbabwean Deputy Finance Minister
Misheck Chinamasa has denied the government was overborrowing
from foreign sources, noting that most of the government
expenditure was raised from tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Chinamasa made the remarks Wednesday while responding to
issues from members of parliament (MPs) attempting to refuse
the ratification of some loan agreements.
</P>
<P>
"The debt service ratio is less than 20 percent," Chinamasa
said. "The recommended debt service ratio is 30 percent which
means that my ministry has been very cautious in its borrowings."
</P>
<P>
He said the MPs should not make conditions, or hold new loans
to ransom in view of the previous loans.
</P>
<P>
A loan of 318 million Zimbabwean Dollars (16 million U.S.
Dollars) which the MPs refused to ratify had been catered for
during the last budget announced last year and was indicated as
net foreign borrowing, said the deputy minister.
</P>
<P>
It contributed to less than one percent as most of the
government's expenditure was raised from tax revenue, he said. It
was not true that the government was overborrowing from foreign
sources, he added.
</P>
<P>
The house, however, for the second day running refused to
ratify the loans.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government's total external debt by June 30
last year stood at 28.9 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (about 1.5
billion U.S. Dollars), the Zimbabwe News Agency Thursday quoted
the deputy minister as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
