<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Thursday said his government is committed to the education
of girl child despite the country's financial hardship.
</P>
<P>
"Despite financial hardships, the government has allocated 4
percent of the Gross National Product (GNP) during the current
fiscal year to the education sector," Sharif told a foundation
stone-laying ceremony of the first women university in the country
Thursday in Rawalpindi, about 20 km south of here.
</P>
<P>
"This is double the amount specified during last fiscal year,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government, instead of having an "eye on the
national exchequer, is committed to spending the money on the
education of girl child.
</P>
<P>
The first women university has been named after illustrious
sister of the father of the nation and will be known as "Fatima
Jinnah Women University", he said, adding it will accommodate
about 4,000 women students.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that he specially instructed the
authorities to specify 10 percent quota for those girls who could
not afford to continue their studies.
</P>
<P>
"These 400 girl students will be given scholarships and all
their expenses will be met by the government," he declared.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's official literacy rate is about 30 percent and is
one of the lowest in the world. The literacy rate of the women
population is even lower. 
</P>
