<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks fell sharply
on Thursday to finish at a three-year-odd low, as the market was
feeling the pinch of higher interbank rates and a weaker Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index fell 212.07 points, or 2.84 percent, to
close at 7,254.36, the lowest since January 25, 1995, when the
index ended at 7,240.72.
</P>
<P>
The market opened 10 points higher on the heels of overnight
recovery on the Wall Street but soon lost steam. At the morning
close, the index slipped 112.60 points, or 1.51 percent to
7,353.83.
</P>
<P>
The fall came as interbank rates went up over fears of another
round of speculative attacks on the local currency, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
A weaker Japanese yen and a poor earnings report made by
conglomerate Swire Pacific also drove the market down.
</P>
<P>
Swire Pacific, one of the 33 constituent stocks of the Hang
Seng Index, reported Wednesday a 39 percent decline in profits for
the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The value of turnover amounted to 4,745 million HK dollars (608
million U.S. dollars), against the previous day's 4,946 million HK
dollars (634 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
