<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- This capital of east China's
Fujian Province has mobilized all possible forces to contribute to
the re-employment of displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou launched 20 large-scale labor fairs in the first half of
this year, re-employing 22,000 laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates have put Fuzhou's number of laid-off workers
from state-owned and collective enterprises at 49,000 this
year. The city government has vowed to help find jobs for at least
30,000, keeping the registered unemployment rate below 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
This year Fuzhou has unveiled a large number of preferential
policies to facilitate the re-employment of laid-off workers. The
city federation of trade unions, in cooperation with related
departments, has opened China's first telephone hot line
especially for re-employment purposes. Some 87 companies and
schools have provided technical training for nearly 3,000 laid-off
workers without any charge.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more than 400 enterprises in Fuzhou have
promised to give prior consideration to displaced workers. 
