<HEADLINE> Flood Diversion Unnecessary at Jingjiang River Dikes, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese flood control authorities
confirmed today that, so far, it is not necessary to blow up the
Jinjiang River Dikes in Hubei Province to divert the Yangtze River
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the present situation, there is no need to take
that step," said Zhao Chunming, deputy director of the office of
the state's Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters, in
answer to questions at this afternoon's news conference.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not rule out the possibility of diverting the
flood at the Jingjiang River section if the situation there
continues to worsen.
</P>
<P>
In 1954, when the Yangtze River suffered serious floods, the
Jingjiang River Dikes had to be blown up for flood
diversion. Since then, this section of the Yangtze River has
become a sensitive issue whenever serious flooding occurs.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that the dikes and embankment of the Yangtze River
have been significantly reinforced during past decades, and are
now capable of containing floods more serious than that of 1954.
</P>
<P>
However, preparations are being made in the Jingjiang River
diversion area in case there is a need to divert the floodwaters,
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
