<HEADLINE> 100 Rebel Soldiers of Congo (k) Enter Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one hundred Banyamulenge
rebel soldiers of the Democratic Republic of Congo have fled into
Zambia and surrendered to the security forces in the last
two days.
</P>
<P>
Zambian government spokesman David Mpamba confirmed the
developments, and said that Zambia has closed temporarily two
northern border transit points in Kasumbalesa and Mokambo to
tighten the screening of the people entering the country, Zambia
Daily Mail reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, nearly 100 Banyamulenge soldiers
arrived in Kitwe and Chingola in Zambia's Northern Province
Tuesday. And another 20 rebel soldiers arrived in Mufulira where
they are now under guard at the city's police station.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the Banyamulenge rebels now in Kitwe, Jerome
Tambwe, appealed on Wednesday to the Zambian government to
repatriate them to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the paper, Tambwe said the rwandese fled
Congo (K) after the Laurent Kabila government attempted to
disarm them before they entered Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He said that some congolese soldiers are being demoted on
tribal lines while the Banyamulenge soldiers are asked to go back
to Rwanda, alleging that they are foreigners. 
</P>
