<HEADLINE> Zambia Not Undermining Angola Peace Process: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
refuted South African media reports that Zambia is undermining
the Angolan peace process by supporting the rebel movement of
Angola.
</P>
<P>
It is preposterous for anybody to suggest that Zambia will
work to undermine the Angolan peace process it helped to bring
about in 1994, President Frederick Chiluba's aide, Richard
Sakala, said in an interview with the Southern African
Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) in Lusaka Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The international verification teams have visited Zambia
several times and in all cases found it not guilty of the
allegations, the Times of Zambia newspaper Thursday quoted Sakala
as saying.
</P>
<P>
South African media reports have stated that Angola is getting
impatient with Zambia because of its perceived support for the
rebel National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
forces.
</P>
<P>
Sakala noted that the reports have come up at a time when
relations between Zambia and Angola are "warm and cordial".
</P>
<P>
He said: " Zambia has hosted official Angolan delegations that
have visited our border to establish the truth of these
allegations, which in many cases have emanated from press reports
in South Africa."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports in South Africa suggested that UNITA has
secured arms supply lines through Zambia by capturing the town of
Luau in Angola's Moxico Province, giving it easy access to arms
through Zambia, said the Zambian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Sakala denied such arms supply lines through Zambia, saying
that Zambia is keen to ensure peace in Angola for economic,
social and political reasons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
