<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aussi Tech to Be Used to Dispose of U.S. Plutonium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Australian technology will help
keep surplus United States weapons-grade plutonium safely
immobilized, the Australian federal government announced here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Australian Science and Industry Minister John Moore announced
the deal with the U.S. Department of Energy Thursday in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Soviet-U.S. nuclear arms race left a legacy of
weapons-grade plutonium which the superpowers have agreed to
reduce," Moore said.
</P>
<P>
The project would use a Synroc-based ceramic.
</P>
<P>
Synroc, developed by the late Professor Ted Ringwood of the
Australian National University and further refined at Australian
Nuclear Science and Technology Organization (ANSTO), is an
advanced ceramic made of titanate minerals which immobilize
radioactive elements in nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
Moore said ANSTO had been working for about four years with the
designated lead laboratory for developing immobilization
technology in the U.S., the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
in California, to come up with the best ceramic material for the
job.
</P>
<P>
"Although it has taken a long time for Synroc to be
implemented, I am confident it will now come into its own and be
used extensively in other radioactive waste management projects,"
Moore said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
