<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Continue Hitting S.Korea, 23 killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
Thursday directed government departments to spare no efforts to
minimize human casualties and property damage caused by continuing
heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Canceling his planned visit to North and South Kyongsang
provinces, the president especially ordered Seoul mayor and governor
of Kyonggi province to take effective measures to fight against the
rains.
</P>
<P>
The continuing rains have disrupted rail traffic, swollen waterways
and inundated houses and roads in Seoul and its surrounding areas
since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three people, including nine servicemen, were reportedly
dead in the torrential rains Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said nine soldiers were killed by a landslide
caused by the rain when they were working to restore a communication
network Thursday in northern Seoul.
</P>
<P>
A rescue operation is still under way for three soldiers buried
under rubble after a landslide engulfed their guard posts, said the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a landslide, which devoured a restauant in northern
Seoul Thursday morning, killed six people and left other five missing.
</P>
<P>
Inchon is the hardest hit area so far with a rainfall of 616 mm,
which has claimed one life and left six missing Thursday morning. All
passenger boat service from Inchon were suspended due to heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Some 9,746 hectares of farmland and parts of over 5,700 building
are submerged in rain water in Kyonggi Province when rains are still
pouring hard, killing seven and leaving 2,700 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Disaster Headquarters said the number casualties and
damages will rise as at least 100 mm more rain is expected to fall
late Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
