<HEADLINE> Steady Economic Growth In Eastern China In First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
reported 209 billion yuan in gross domestic product in the first
half of the year, a rise of 9.4 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
This is largely attributed to the increased investment,
according to Chen Daxin, head of Zhejiang Provincial Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises spent 31 billion yuan on fixed assets
from January to June, a rise of 23.6 percent from the same period
last year. The province had 91.79 billion yuan in retail sales in
the first half, up 8 percent. It also did 7.06 billion
U.S. dollars worth of foreign trade, a rise of 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The province also approved 482 overseas-backed enterprises,
with contracts worth 880 million U.S. dollars. Both figures are
increases from last year.
</P>
<P>
By June, bank savings in the province were 45.96 billion yuan
more than that at the beginning of the year, and 19.97 billion
yuan was loaned in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that Zhejiang will continue to do well in economic
performance in the latter half because of increased fixed assets
investment and macro-economic measures starting to take effect and
it is expected to meet this year's goal of 8 percent
growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
