<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Business Confidence Drops Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South African business
confidence took a knock for the third successive month, slumping
1.9 percent in July, said a senior official of the South African
Chamber of Business (Sacob).
</P>
<P>
The decline of 1.9 percent last month after falls of 1.2
percent and 5.7 percent in May and June showed that the South
African economy remained vulnerable to both internal and external
pressures as well as the aftershock of currency instability which
began in late May, the Business Day newspaper Thursday quoted
Sacob saying.
</P>
<P>
Sacob economic policy director, Ben van Rensburg, said that the
continual business mood of uncertainty reflected a weaker
economic outlook, higher interest rates, slackening internal
demand and South Africa's emerging-market risk profile, with the
resultant dampening effect on potential foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"The concern of business that real interest will remain at its
present levels and therefore higher than originally anticipated,
contributed to the weakening of business confidence," van
Rensburg said.
</P>
<P>
The prime lending rates of commercial banks now stands at 24
percent and mortgage rates at 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Van Rensburg said the recent financial developments would lead
to slower economic growth and Sacob had revised its growth rate
forecast down to one percent for this year.
</P>
<P>
However, Sacob believed that the economy would grow by between
two and 2.5 percent next year as stability returned and the
impact of the demutualization of Sanlam and Old Mutual, two major
insurance companies, became evident.
</P>
<P>
Just two months before the Rand began to slide, South Africa
had been rated as one of the most attractive investment
opportunities in the emerging economies, but global developments
were working slowly against the assessment, van Rensburg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
