<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ashrawi Resigns From Arafat's Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hanan Ashrawi, the
newly-appointed Minister of Tourism and Archaeology in the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), resigned on Thursday to
protest the lack of reform in the cabinet reshuffle made by PNA
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in the West Bank city Ramallah,
Ashrawi said she would continue to stay in the Palestinian
Legislative Council (PLC), and would contribute her knowledge and
wisdom to it as an elected member.
</P>
<P>
Her move was apparently in protest against the failure by
Arafat to tackle the widely reported corruption within the
cabinet, which was the main reason behind the latest cabinet
shakeup.
</P>
<P>
Arafat on Wednesday presented the lineup of his new cabinet to
the PLC for approval. But to the disappointment of his critics,
all the ministers accused of being corrupt in the previous cabinet
retained their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi, who served as Minister of Higher Education, was
transferred to the post of tourism and archaeology.
</P>
<P>
She said she rejected Arafat's offer because "I believe that
comprehensive reform was not addressed in this new government
formulation."
</P>
<P>
Before announcing her resignation, Ashrawi held a long meeting
Wednesday night with Arafat to explain here reason to quit. She
said the Palestinian people are facing a very difficult time both
at home and abroad, and to face the challenge needs comprehensive
reform in the government.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed discontent with the way of handling the
peace negotiations with Israel by the Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian talks have been stalled since early
last year due to Israel's expansion of settlements and delay in
carrying out troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Ashrawi added that she respects Arafat very much and still
supports him to seek peace for the entire Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi gained her world fame as the spokeswoman for the
Palestinian delegation during the Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
As a former professor of English at Bir Zeit University in
Ramallah, she was elected to the PLC in the first Palestinian
election in early 1996 .
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi comes from a prominent Palestinian Christian family and
has wrote several books in both English and Arabic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
