<HEADLINE> Man Suspected Of Involvement In Taiwanese Woman's Death Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAICHENG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Police in the northeast China
province of Liaoning have arrested a Liaoning man, Zhang Shifeng,
who is suspected of being involved in the death of Lin Ti-chuan, a
Taiwanese woman who was killed while on a business trip to the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Zhang was apprehended at about 11 a.m. this morning on a train
going from Yantai in east China's Shangdong Province to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Another suspect in the case, Huang Shidong, a farmer from the
city of Haicheng, was caught in Mulan County in Heilongjiang
Province on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
So far police have ascertained that the kidnapping of the woman
was plotted by a Haicheng businessman, Li Guangzhi, and was
carried out by by Huang, Zhang, and two other men, Yang Rongxi and
Zhao Chuang.
</P>
<P>
Huang has confessed during an interrogation that he and the
others abducted Lin Ti-chuan and a Taiwanese businessman named Wei
Tien-kang, and took them to an empty room in the Haicheng
Development Zone on the evening of July 27, soon after their
arrival in the port city of Dalian in Liaoning. The motive was an
attempt to force Wei to return some money that he owed Li.
</P>
<P>
Yang Rongxi gave both Wei and Lin several injections to knock
them out, and Lin began to suffer respiratory difficulties and
turned pale 11 a.m. on July 29. Huang then sent Lin to a local
hospital in Haicheng, where he discovered that Lin had died, and
fled.
</P>
<P>
The police are now making all-out efforts to search for the
other people who may be involved in the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
