<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Victorian State to Regulate Traditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Victorian state
government Thursday announced a plan to regulate the practice of
Traditional Chinese medicine (TCM).
</P>
<P>
Victorian Premier Jeff Kennett announced the plan to develop a
legislative framework in Melbourne, on the basis of a 1995
Department of Human Services (DHS) report, capital of the state.
</P>
<P>
"Victoria is the first jurisdiction outside China to adopt a
comprehensive regulatory regime for TCM," he told guests at the
launch of the report.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Broadcasting Corporation said other states or
territories in Australia, or even the Australian federal
government, and other Western nations may follow suit if the
framework would be passed by the state parliament as law.
</P>
<P>
"Through the adoption of the recommendations in this report we
will ensure a regulatory framework that is a response to the needs
of both the community and practitioners," said the premier.
</P>
<P>
Robert Doyle, the Victorian government's parliamentary
secretary for health, said TCM had become an increasingly popular
form of health care with an estimated 2.8 million consultations
each year representing an annual turnover of over 48 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new laws will be designed to protect the public, ensuring
practitioners have a minimum qualification.
</P>
<P>
Professor T. Chiang Lin, president of the Federation of the
Chinese Medicine Association, described the practice as "a
treasure of modern civilization" and thanked Kennett for his
active involvement in regulating the profession.
</P>
<P>
"Victoria is providing leadership to the rest of Australia and
internationally," he told the assembled guests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
