<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't, Rebels to Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) will resume peace talks
in a southern city on August 18 to tackle some substantive issues,
the government's chief negotiator said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are not only opening the door towards peace, but we are
opening wider so that we can accommodate more thoughts toward the
attainment of peace in Mindanao," retired Lt. Gen. Orlando Soriano
said.
</P>
<P>
Soriano was speaking to reporters when signing an agreement
with the MNLF calling for both sides to refrain from conducting
combat operations while the peace talks are underway.
</P>
<P>
Alunan Glang, who signed the agreement on behalf of the MILF,
said that the group is "determined to pursue these negotiations
until the successful conclusion is reached with goodwill on both
sides."
</P>
<P>
Soriano said that the government is working hard for the
successful conclusion of the peace talks and "we certainly also
appreciate the efforts being done by our MILF brothers towards
attaining peace."
</P>
<P>
The MILF, headed by Hashim Salamat, is a breakaway faction of
the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) which signed a peace
accord with the government in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government has been negotiating with the MILF to sign a
separate peace agreement. The MILF is basically based in Central
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Low-level peace talks between the government and the MILF
started in January 1997 but were suspended by the MILF during the
presidential elections held in May this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
