<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Expected to Help Counter Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese flood-control official
today reaffirmed the expected positive role of the Three Gorges
Project in flood control.
</P>
<P>
The big dam of the giant Three Gorges Project, if now in use,
would have helped to intercept floods in the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River, Zhao Chunming, an official of the General Office of
the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters, told a
news conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"If there were the big dam this year, the water level in the
lower reaches would not have been that high and the flood control
task would not have been that arduous," he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is essential to build the big dam and the Three
Gorges Project, Zhao told journalists at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts to conserve water and soil and to prevent
and control soil erosion, he said, the ecological environment in
the Three Gorges area is good overall.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project, which began in December of 1994, is
situated on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River and is a major
part of China's effort to develop the country's longest river. The
Damming of the river for construction of the project was completed
last November, and the whole project will take 17 years to
complete.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
