<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Traditional Artwork Being Smuggled (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, August 6, (Xinhua) - A Chinese legislative
sub-committee has found that an increasing number of valuable
works of art created by Chinese ethnic minorities over thousands
of years are being smuggled out the country.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Education, Sciences, Culture and Public
Health under the National People's Congress is also proposing
related laws to counter this crime.
</P>
<P>
In a recent investigative tour of Northwest China's Gansu
Province, rich in history and diverse in ethnic minority
inhabitants, the sub-committee found that "an astonishing amount"
of leather-silhouette show tools, paper-cutting products, wood
sculpture, brick sculpture, Hui embroideries and Tibetan
traditional dress and personal adornment are being lost to
collectors in Japan, Korea and some American and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
These works of art, which are dying inside China because of
economic development, are representative of the culture of
northwest China and unique to the tradition of the ethnic
minorities who produced them.
</P>
<P>
The investigative team found that "overseas organizations and
individuals, including business people, scholars and students are
flocking to places home to rich cultural legacies to collect those
items or even buy them at unusually high prices."
</P>
<P>
"Those collectors seem to be well-organized and are
well-planned," an official with the sub-committee said, noting
that they go to villages not only fishing for paper-cutting
products and Tibetan cloth pictures, but also buying traditional
tools such as steel for flint.
</P>
<P>
"That's no longer individual hobby or interests; it's cultural
robbery," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
