<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Traditional Artwork Being Smuggled (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Koreans reportedly are accumulating legacies of China's
Dongxiang nationality, and the Japanese Folk Custom Society
declared 10 years ago its intent to amass Chinese materials for
its study.
</P>
<P>
Qingyang Prefecture of Gansu Province is known for its
traditional leather-silhouette show. The sub-committee has learned
the oldest set of leather-silhouette show equipment dating back to
the late Qing Dynasty was bought by a tourist from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The sub-committee said that, because there is no related laws,
it is impossible to curb the smuggling trend. Some localities are
even relying on foreign buyers as a source of income.
</P>
<P>
The outcome is that it is hard to find these valuables in
China while foreign people are opening museums and exhibitions of
those items, the sub-committee said. China's existing law on
cultural relics does not cover the protection of all the cultural
legacies of ethnic minorities, the investigative team said.
</P>
<P>
"So it is necessary for China to garner efforts to make laws
in this respect," it stressed, advocating that a special expert
committee should be established to assess all the traditional
items of artistic creation of ethnic minorities, and localities
should also formulate regulations based on their own need "to ease
the present acute situation."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
