<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tropical Storms to Hit Southeast China in Near Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Four to six tropical cyclones or
typhoons may come into being over northwest Pacific and South
China Sea, of which two or three may land in the southeast coast
of China from now to the end of August.
</P>
<P>
In the coming 10 days, the major rain-belts are expected to
linger over the eastern part of north China, most areas in
northeast China, the areas between Yellow and Huaihe rivers, the
eastern part of southwest China and the coastal areas in both
south and southeast China, Yan Hong, deputy head of the Central
Meteorological Administration, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Two or three tropical cyclones are expected to develop over
northwest Pacific and South China Sea, of which one or two is
likely to affect or land in the coastal areas in south and
southeast China,
</P>
<P>
In addition, the areas between Yangtze and Huaihe rivers, the
south of Yangtze River and South China will expect weather with
little rain but high temperature, estimated at between 34 and 38
centimeters degree, may continue for four to six days.
</P>
<P>
More tropical cyclones are anticipated from August to October
this year. An estimated 14 to 18 tropical cyclones may develop, of
which four to six may make landfall in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
The China Meteorological Administration and its subordinate
meteorological offices at various levels have been paying close
attention to the above-mentioned abnormal changes of weather and
climate in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
