<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Gets Compensation For Arm Bitten Off by Bear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 6, (Xinhua) -- Wei Xingyu, a 9-year-old boy
whose left arm was bitten by a brown bear and later amputated, was
entitled to compensation of 560,000 yuan (69,000 U.S. dollars),
according to a ruling by the Sichuan Provincial Higher People's
Court.
</P>
<P>
On Aug. 20, 1996, Lin Jianqiong, who is the boy's aunt, took
him to Qionghai Park where she worked in Xichang County, Liangshan
Autonomous Prefecture of Yi Nationalities, in southwest China's
Sichuan Province. While he was at the park, a bear bit Wei's left
arm while he was feeding the bear with grass. The accident forced
the amputation of the boy's left arm, today's Shanghai-based "Wen
Hui Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
After the tragedy happened, the Liangshan Prefecture's
Intermediate People's Court conducted the initial trial, but the
plaintiff and defendants refused to accept the ruling and lodged
appeals to a higher court.
</P>
<P>
The Sichuan Provincial Higher People's Court ruled that
Qionghai Park and the boy's temporary guardian, Lin Jianqiong,
should pay the plaintiff a compensation fee of 450,819 yuan and
112,705 yuan, respectively, within 30 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies Barring U.N. Inspectors From Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq denied Thursday that it had
banned a U.N. arms inspection team from entering a weapons site
here, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An official source at the Iraqi National Monitoring
Directorate was quoted as saying there was no question of Iraq's
banning U.N. inspection teams from carrying out their duties
because "there is no arms inspection team in Iraq right now."
</P>
<P>
"All the U.N. arms inspectors here belong to long-term
monitoring teams," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that according to Wednesday's decision made by the
Iraqi government, activities of the long-term monitoring teams are
allowed to continue, and in fact all monitoring activities are
going on smoothly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that an inspection team of the U.N. Special
Commission for disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, was refused access
to an Iraqi weapons site Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi government announced Wednesday it would freeze
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors in protest against the
eight year long crippling U.N. sanctions imposed after the 1990
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
It conditioned the resumption of the cooperation on the
reestablishment of the UNSCOM and other changes regarding the
U.N. weapons inspection mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq said all U.N. monitoring activities will be allowed on
the conditions that U.N. monitors must respect Iraq's sovereignty,
security and its people's dignity.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi decision to freeze cooperation with UNSCOM was
made following the breakdown of the latest round of talks held
between UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Aziz refused to continue the talks to protest Butler's refusal
to give a clean bill of health on Iraq's weapons programs, a
condition set by the U.N. for the lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The seven year long U.N. inspection mission has been marred by
repeated confrontations between Iraq and the U.S., which has been
taking a tough stance on destroying Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq charges the U.S. for ignoring the progress already made in
the inspection in an attempt to prolong the crippling economic
sanctions, that have banned the free sale of oil, Iraq's economic
lifelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
