<HEADLINE> Another Yangtze Flood Peak Approaching Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The fourth flood peak on the
mainstream of the Yangtze River is moving downstream toward
Yichang in central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
A report from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters shows that the water level at Yichang rose to 53.06
meters at 5 a.m. this morning, 1.06 meters higher than the danger
mark, with a flow rate of 53,700 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the section between Yichang and Luoshan is
rising 0.07-to-0.46 meters daily, while that between Shashi and
Luoshan has surpassed the all-time high.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Dongting Lake rose to 35.38 meters at 6 this
morning, 0.12 meters higher than Wednesday and 0.07 meters higher
than the previous record.
</P>
<P>
But water levels on sections downstream of Hankou, including
Poyang Lake, have begun to fall. However, the level at the lake
was still measured at 22.3 meters at 6 a.m., 0.5 meters higher
than the all-time high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
