<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Flooding on Northeast China's Nenjiang River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- New flooding has occurred on
northeast China's Nenjiang River because of more rainfall during
the past few days which caused the water level to rise in the main
stream of the river.
</P>
<P>
By 2 a.m. today, the water level recorded at Gannan
hydrological station in Heilongjiang Province rose to 169.88
meters, 0.03 meters more than the safety level. The water flow
monitored was 5,460 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
The increased water flow on the Nenjiang River has also
increased water levels at hydrological stations on the Songhua
River.
</P>
<P>
The water level monitored at Songyuan hydrological station in
Jilin Province was 99.29 meters by 5 this morning, 1.04 meters
more than the danger line, and the water flow was 7,350 cubic
meters per second.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Harbin hydrological Station rose to 118.41
meters by 6 a.m. today, 0.31 meters more than the danger line,
with a water flow of 6,670 cubic meters per second.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
