<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Gunman Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- One Lebanese anti-Israeli
guerrilla fighter was killed and another wounded Thursday night by
Israeli artillery shelling in south Lebanon, the Orient Radio
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The killed was an officer of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
He was burnt to death after the car he was driving caught fire
after being struck by an Israeli shell on the road between Zibqine
and Jebal al-Butom in the north of Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The latest killing brought to 24 the death toll of Hezbollah
fighters in south Lebanon so far this year. In the same period,
nine Israeli soldiers have been killed in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
settlements from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Lebanese resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting with Israel's occupation forces and
its allied South Lebanon Army in a bid to oust them from the
country. 
</P>
