<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Bring Heavy Loss Of Lives and Properties To China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Seasonal floods, accompanied by
landslides and mud-flows have claimed a relatively heavy loss of
lives and brought enormous economic losses to China, a senior
Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Civil Affairs Fan Baojun told a news
conference that 240 million people in 28 provinces, municipalities
and autonomous regions have been affected by the floods,
with 13.8 million people relocated to safe places, 5.58 million
houses destroyed, and 12.05 million houses suffering damages.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 21.53 million ha. of farmland were affected,
including 4.78 million ha. of farmlands with their crops totally
destroyed, according to the vice-minister.
</P>
<P>
The central government has provided more than 1.9 billion yuan
worth of relief funds and large quantities of relief materials to
the flood-affected areas, and local governments in 12 provinces
and municipalities have allocated 720 million yuan for the same
purpose.
</P>
<P>
The local governments have distributed nearly 290,000 tons of
cereals and 6.31 million pieces of wears and covers to flood
victims, while 346,000 make-shifts have been erected for those who
have been made homeless by the floods, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Fan pledged that each of the flood victims will receive a half
kg of grain every day.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have also mobilized people to make donations
to the flood victims. So far, Hunan and Hubei, the two most
affected provinces, have got 47 million yuan in cash and 41.8
million yuan in kind, he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister paid tribute to the army, police and reserve
servicemen for the remarkable role they have played in battling
against the floods. Meanwhile, he noted, the troops and policemen
have also made large amount of donations.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government will work hard to implement the
rehabilitation programs and build winter-shelters for the
homeless, and the flood victims will get their winter clothing and
quilts from the government and donors, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also assured that all donations will be properly used as
efforts will be made to step up supervision and management over
the distribution of donations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contaminated Water Kills 12 Children in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- As many as 12 children have
died and over 100 taken ill in a slum cluster in west Delhi during
the past 10 days due to suspected contaminated water supplied by
private water tankers, the Statesman daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The children had complained of loose motions, vomiting and in
some cases, fever after drinking the water, described by a local
dweller as raw and yellow in color.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary inquiry by district administration pointed out
that the water was supplied to the dwellers by two private
contractors at the instance of the Delhi Development Authority
(DDA).
</P>
<P>
The dwellers, about 900, had been relocated in Kakrola in west
Delhi last month by the DDA from a park in the city, according to
the Statesman.
</P>
<P>
Delhi Chief Minister Sahib Singh has ordered an inquiry into
the death of the children by the deputy commissioner of South-West
District.
</P>
<P>
The Central Pollution Control Board said last Sunday that water
supply in New Delhi was "unsafe" for drinking and it did not meet
the standards prescribed by the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
According to a report submitted by the board to Delhi High
Court, samples of raw and treated water collected in April this
year indicated the presence of pesticides. And the Yamuna river, a
main water source for the capital, was seriously polluted with
organic matter and fecal coliform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
