<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives to Reduce Flood Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The joint efforts of Chinese
people from all walks of life have ensured the safety of major
rivers and lakes and leading cities and railways, cutting the
losses to the minimum level, according to a senior flood control
official.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of floods in many parts of China,
governments at all levels have made flood control the focal point
of their work, Zhou Wenzhi, secretary-general of the State Flood
Control and Drought Relief Headquarters, told a press conference
here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the close cooperation between various departments
and the concerted efforts of soldiers and the general public, the
safety of the embankments of major rivers and lakes and leading
cities and railways have been guaranteed and the flood losses have
been reduced to the minimum," said Zhou, who is also vice-minister
of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
Frequent spells of torrential rains have ravaged most parts of
eastern and southern China since mid-June, with some areas in
northern China also hit by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The massive precipitation resulted in big floods in the Yangtze
River, the Poyang and Tongting lakes, the Pear River, the
Minjiang River, and the Songhuajiang River. In many rivers, the
water level or water flow has hit an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
For more than a month, the water level in parts of the
Yangtze River and the Tongting and Boyang lakes has exceeded
the safety line.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the water level of the Yangtze River remains high
and that of the Songhua River has not yet receded, Zhou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
