<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean Price Down to Four-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Soybean futures Wednesday
fell close to four-year lows on the Chicago Board of Trade,
weighed down by expectations for large supplies and weak demand,
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Soybeans for November delivery, representing prices after the
fall harvest, fell 6.5 cents to 5.4125 U.S. dollar a bushel, the
lowest since October 1994.
</P>
<P>
Market sources say there were several factors behind the
remarkable drop of soybean prices.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, they pointed out, the beneficial rains in U.S. Midwest
and some Southern growing regions appeared to all-but-seal
expectations that farmers this fall will harvest the largest crop
on record.
</P>
<P>
Some market participants are speculating the crop's size could
top 3 billion bushels, much higher than 2.83 billion bushel
estimated by U.S. Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, there has been large supplies in the international
markets. Brazil, Argentina and other major soybean growing
countries all had large harvests last year which created abundant
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Finally, there are few overseas takers because of Asian
economic woes. Market analysts believe that Asian demand will
continue to be weak or dried up in the coming year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel is Losing Grip Over Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., a colossus of
chipmakers, is losing its vice-like grip over the business, a new
study released today.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of businesses in the United States say they
are willing to consider buying computers powered by chips made by
Intel's rivals, according to the July survey by ZD Market
Intelligence, a market analysis firm based in California.
</P>
<P>
About 34 percent of 2,624 U.S. businesses showed interest in
PCs with AMD or Cyrix chips instead of Intel-based processors,
while 27 percent said they were "highly motivated" to buy either
AMD or Cyrix powered computers.
</P>
<P>
For years, Intel has controlled over 90 percent of the consumer
and business markets for processors. But now AMD and Cyrix account
for a combined 60 percent of the market for desktops selling under
1,000 U.S. dollars and 38 percent of total X86 desktop PCs selling
in the U.S. retail channel in June. In June 1997, only five
percent of total desktop PCs sold in retail used non-Intel
chips.
</P>
<P>
Computer customers nowadays do not care what the brand of
processor inside the computer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Low in Carbon Monoxide Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand emits below the
average levels for carbon monoxide and sulphur oxide, but over the
average level for nitrogen oxide on a per capita basis, according
to the set standards by the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
A Statistics New Zealand's report, which was released here
Thursday noted that open fires were a major source of urban air
pollution in a number of New Zealand cities and towns, with almost
23 percent of all households in 1996 still using this form of home
heating. But the report said that the number of homes with open
fires has been declining steadily.
</P>
<P>
According to other environmental statistics provided in the
report, New Zealand's methane output is relatively high for the
size of the country, due to its agriculture base and subsequent
emissions from livestock. Its per capital emissions of methane are
nine times the global average.
</P>
<P>
Carbon dioxide concentrations over the southern hemisphere are
presently increasing at a rate of approximately 0.4 percent per
year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that further ozone depletion will continue
till the end of this century. "The next five to 10 years will see
the greatest damage to the ozone layer," the report warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0220 </DOCNO>
