<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Undertake Program for Flood-Hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
approved 81.2 million taka (about 1.73 million U.S. dollars) for
an emergency agriculture rehabilitation program in the
flood-affected areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
This allocation was approved Wednesday by the Ministry of
Finance upon the proposals of the Agriculture Ministry, a press
report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The money would be used for providing assistance to small and
marginal farmers in their rehabilitation work after havoc caused
by heavy flood since early the July-October monsoon season.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, about 420,000 hectares of cropland in 55 of the
country's 64 districts have been damaged due to flooding caused by
incessant rains, onrush of hilly waters and waters from across the
borders.
</P>
<P>
Besides, more than 17.4 million people have been affected by
the flood, which has also damaged and washed away 5,100 kilometers
of roads, 2,396 kilometers of embankment with 2,215 bridges and
culverts and perished nearly 6,000 cattle, according to
preliminary estimates.
</P>
<P>
The government departments concerned have so far distributed
more than 13.2 million taka (about 280,850 dollars), nearly 30,000
tons of grain and other relief materials to the flood-hit people.
</P>
<P>
The overall flood situation in the country is improving as
water in the major rivers is receding gradually, though the
situation might deteriorate again in northern and northwestern
areas of the Ganges and Brahmaputra basins and upper parts of the
Meghna basin, according to the Flood Information Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
