<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lin Ti-Chuan Relatives Affirm Help from Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- "I'm very, very grateful for all
the Haicheng side has done for us," the father of Lin Ti-chuan,
the Taiwan woman killed in Haicheng city in Liaoning Province,
said today.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his gratitude at a farewell breakfast held in
Haicheng.
</P>
<P>
The grieving father, who had been silent for days here, showed
his feelings today to the Taiwan Affairs Office of Liaoning
Province, saying loudly: "Thank you! thank you all!"
</P>
<P>
Another Lin relative said at the breakfast that "through the
handling of the aftermath of Miss Lin Ti-chuan's tragedy, I feel
that the ties between the people across the Taiwan Straits are
closer."
</P>
<P>
He said he will tell the Kaohsiung public when he returns how
they were received and treated cordially by the people of Haicheng.
</P>
<P>
He also invited Chen Yonghao, deputy director of the provincial
Taiwan Affairs Office, to visit Taiwan, saying,"I will treat you."
</P>
<P>
Lin's remains were transported to Beijing at 6:00 a.m. this
morning and will be returned to Taiwan via Hong Kong at the
request of Lin's family.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Babaoshan International Remains Transportation
Department changed its Beijing-Macao-Taiwan schedule because of a
request from Lin's family that her remains be returned to
Kaohsiung by sunset.
</P>
<P>
Two hours after the agreement was reached yesterday afternoon,
11 of Lin's relatives said that they would leave Haicheng this
morning via Shenyang for Beijing. However, since they did not have
the proper travel documents, according to Chinese rules they were
required to exit by Dalian, from which they had entered.
</P>
<P>
However, the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Straits (ARATS), the provincial Taiwan Affairs Office, and the
local government worked overnight to have their travel documents
prepared and air tickets ready.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Lin's parents said that they also expected to be
accommodated at a hotel near Babaoshan, and be offered ideal
places to chant Buddhist sutras for mourning their daughter at
5:00 a.m. in the morning and 5:00 p.m. in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
When they were ready to leave Haicheng, they were told, "all
set," and Lin's parents and relatives left Haicheng at 9:00
a.m. today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
