<HEADLINE> Flood-Stricken Hubei Province Declares State Of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province has
declared a state of emergency beginning at 8:00 am today to combat
rampant flooding fueled by the latest round of torrential rains to
hit the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
This decision by the provincial government was made in
accordance with the Anti-Flood Law.
</P>
<P>
Under this law, local flood control headquarters are empowered
to make decisions during the emergency period on flood-related
matters such as removing obstacles from roads and bridges,
mobilizing materials, vehicles and laborers, and taking control of
communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, water levels in the province
have surpassed historic highs in most parts of the Yangtze, with
the water level at the Jianli Hydrometric Station reaching 37.81
meters at 8:00 pm on Wednesday, exceeding the 1954 record by 1.24
meters.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has given a do-or-die order to local
people to safeguard major cities and dykes along the Yangtze and
its tributary Lianjiang River.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, the local government of Jinjiang City
gave up six small dikes in order to concentrate its manpower on
protecting the main Yangtze dikes, and some 100,000 local
residents have been relocated to safe places, according to a local
report.
</P>
<P>
The water levels of the Yangtze are expected to rise still
further due to the formation of this years' fourth flood peak on
the upper reaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
