<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Surgeons Introduce New Procedure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in central China's Hunan
Province have successfully completed a surgical operation on the
heart of a local woman, leaving only a 9-cm scar on her breast.
</P>
<P>
Liao Yan, a patient who was suffering congenital heart
disease, received the operation recently at the Changsha Xiangya
Hospital affiliated to the Human Medical Sciences University.
</P>
<P>
The 9-cm incision was one third of the length of incisions left
by traditional operations for heart diseases, the doctors said. It
stretched from the patient's left armpit to the base of her left
breast and was made at the interval between the ribs.
</P>
<P>
When compared to opening the chest cavity vertically, the new
procedure eliminated the need to remove ribs and thus the length
of the incision was radically reduced.
</P>
<P>
"I'm delighted the operation left only a small scar," said Liao,
adding that the location greatly facilitates post-surgical
care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
