<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Surgery Also Helps Patients Aged over 100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A study released Wednesday
said that people aged over 100 who have operable diseases or
injuries should not be denied surgical interventions because of
their advanced age.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by researchers at the Mayo Foundation in
Rochester, Minnesota, and appeared in the August issue of the
Journal of the American Geriatrics Society, said that the Mayo
team examined the medical records of 31 Minnesota patients, aged
100 to 107 years at the time of surgery.
</P>
<P>
All of the patients, two old men and 29 old women, underwent a
total of 42 operations requiring anesthesia between 1975 -
1994. The researchers reported that the 2-day, one-month, and
one-year postsurgical death rates were 0 percent, 16.1 percent,
and 35.5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
These survival rates are equivalent to those of individuals of
similar age and background not undergoing surgery, the researchers
added.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the researchers believe surgery is often crucial in
helping centenarians. "People 100 years of age and older without
life-threatening disease may undergo surgical procedures without
further increasing their immediate risk of death," they concluded.
</P>
<P>
The findings are contrary to expectations. Many surgeons are
hesitant to operate on extremely old patients, due to fears that
these "frail" individuals are more harmed than helped by surgical
interventions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that average lifespans continue to rise in many
countries and recent census reports that there are now well over
50,000 centenarians living in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Consumer Goods Market Expected to Grow Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Official statistics show that Shanghai's sales of consumer
goods totaled 71.3 billion yuan in the first six months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has targeted its sales of consumer goods at 147
billion yuan for the whole of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the state policies to stimulate domestic
demand will constitute a favorable factor for the growth of sales
of consumer goods in the second half. The referred policies
include an increase in money supply and medium- and long-term
loans, the effort to reform the fund-raising and investment
practices, increased fiscal support for infrastructure
construction and others.
</P>
<P>
Housing reform will help to activate housing sales and
facilitate the development of related industries, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's increased cooperation with the United States in the
areas of economy, trade and investment, accelerated reform in
state-owned enterprises, and steadily rising incomes of its
residents will also boost sales of consumer goods, they
added.
</P>
<P>
The experts also said that the increasing negative effects of
the Asian financial crisis will be the leading factor affecting
sales of consumer goods in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicate that in the first half of this
year, the growth rate of Shanghai's exports was down 3.2
percentage points from a year ago and investments in Shanghai
from Asian nations and Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan plunged 50
percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A steep drop in the number of tourists from Japan, the Republic
of Korea and other Asian countries has directly affected sales in
industries such as the catering trade, tourism, commerce and
services.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the stock market and residents' increased
non-commodity expenditures such as that on medical care, insurance
and education, and a significant drop in institutional purchasing
power will result in a decline in the flow of money
into the consumer market, experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
