<HEADLINE> Beijing to Publicly Choose High-level Government Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Beijing plans to recruit nearly
1,000 high-level management and technical personnel from the
public this month.
</P>
<P>
The move is an effort to promote reforms in the government
official system, according to a press conference sponsored by the
municipal government yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The some 1,000 to-be-selected officials and high-level
technical personnel will be assigned to positions in charge of
industry, urban construction, commerce and trade, rural areas,
foreign trade, culture and education and health care.
</P>
<P>
The work of openly selecting officials includes three
steps: the first is a free application, along with a public
recommentation; the second is an in-person interview; and the
third, after a strict examination of candidates by the employer,
they will be appointed to positions on a one-year trial basis.
</P>
<P>
The candidates should be under 45 years in age, however, there
some positions for those under the age of 50. All of them should
have permanent residence registration and work experience in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Those with doctorates and masters' degrees obtained at foreign
countries will be given preference in this selection, without any
restriction on their residence registration.
</P>
<P>
Officials currently serving at central government's departments
will also enjoy preferential treatment in this competition,
according to the press conference.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the city selected five government officials at
bureau-chief level through public competition. In 1997, 56
government officials at the same level and advanced management
personnel were recruited in the same way.
</P>
<P>
All of these selected officials and personnel have executed
their responsibilities and reaped achievements in their positions,
according to yesterday's conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
