<HEADLINE> Marine Accidents in First Half Year Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- In the first half of this year,
75 fishermen died or went missing in nearly 200 incidents in east
China sea, Bohai, Yellow, and South China seas, "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The accidents also injured 166 people, damaged 201 fishing
boats and sunk 26 others.
</P>
<P>
"The direct economic losses hit 8.97 million yuan (1.08 million
U.S. dollars), said Shen Jianrong, an official with the Bureau of
Fisheries under the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In east China Sea areas alone, casualties in the first six
months of this year were registered at 155, and at least 70 boats
were damaged or sank.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate report of casualties as Typhoon Otto hit
east China's Fujian Province yesterday.
</P>
<P>
On June 11, a leaking fishing boat from Guangdong's Zhanjiang
City sank with four people aboard; only one was rescued, the rest
were still missing.
</P>
<P>
"We have publicized the cases so that other people may draw
lessons from them," said Zhou Huiming, an official with the south
China sea fishing supervision and management bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau of fisheries has ordered all fishing enterprises to
conduct thorough safety inspections to nip in the bud any snags
that might cause accidents.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance provided 2 million yuan for the
maintenance and construction of the navigation marks as 46 percent
of them erected in 1985 in coastal regions for fishing purposes
have been totally destroyed due to natural or human causes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
