<HEADLINE> Croatian, Slovenian Police Make Big Drug Haul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Croatian police, in a joint
operation with their Slovenian counterparts, seized 38 kilograms
of heroin and cut off a drug-trafficking route from Bosnia to West
Europe, a Croatian Interior Ministry official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The seized drug has a market value of 3.3 million U.S. dollars,
the official told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, Slovenian police were tipped that a drug ring in
Slovenia was planning to ship an unknown amount of drugs from
Bosnia to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The information was quickly passed to Croatian police, who were
asked to intercept vehicles suspected to be involved in drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
On August 1, Croatian police stopped a vehicle at a checkpoint
and found the drug hidden in it.
</P>
<P>
The following day, with information provided by Croatian
police, Slovenian police arrested two people in connection with
the case in Ljubljana, capital of Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
In their homes, police found weapons and evidence allegedly
proving their hand in the case.
</P>
<P>
The heroin was destined for the Netherlands or Spain, the
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
