<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Economy Shows Signs of a Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Polish economy grew by 6.7
percent in the first half of this year over the same period last
year, but it has started to show signs of a slowdown amid worries
over increasing trade deficit and inflation.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of the year, investment went up 23
percent, fueling the fast growth of the economy, while the
nation's unemployment rate dropped to 9.8 percent or 1.69 million,
the lowest since 1991.
</P>
<P>
But a slowdown in the second quarter of the year is threatening
the prospect for a continued economic expansion. The growth rate
of industrial output reached 10.9 percent in the first quarter.
However, it dropped to 6 percent in the second quarter. The growth
of housing sector also slowed down to 16.9 percent in the second
quarter from 25.4 percent in the first one.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade deficit hit 5.9 billion U.S. dollars in the first
half of the year and is expected reach 15.7 billion dollars by the
end of the year, an increase of 39 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the inflation rate had reached 12.2
percent. The government's goal of keeping inflation rate under 9.7
percent appeared to be difficult to achieve by the end of the
year, officials say.
</P>
<P>
The coal industry's output went down by 29.6 percent, compared
with the same period last year. Corporate profit margin dropped
from 1.8 percent in the first quarter to 1.3 percent in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Businesses all over the country borrowed more money, with their
foreign and domestic debt amounting to 50 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the first half of the year, Poland's total foreign debt
increased to about 40 billion dollars from last year's 38.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Large amounts of speculative capital have poured into Poland
because of Russia's turbulent financial situation, the Asian
financial crisis and the continuing strength of the Polish
currency, the Zloty.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, foreign assets in Poland grew by
3 billion dollars, amounting to 26.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
With foreign reserve totaling 25 billion dollars, the Polish
authorities are guarding against a possible financial crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
