<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, U.S. Sign MOU on Disaster Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and the United States
have signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) for a five-year
Humanitarian Assistance Needs Assessment (HANA) project, media
reports here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The HANA project was reportedly to be aimed at helping the
Bangladeshi government minimize natural disaster-caused losses.
</P>
<P>
The MOU was signed here between the two sides on July 29, only
three days after Bangladesh refused to sign the Status of Forces
Agreement (SOFA) with the United States on the ground that SOFA
"would be detrimental to the national interest (of Bangladesh)."
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, a 10-member team of the U.S. Defense Department
came to Bangladesh at the beginning of this month to "assess the
needs of the government to deal with the natural calamity and how
best the United States can contribute on this point," the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
After about three weeks' preliminary assessment, the U.S. team
would nominate projects and submit its recommendations to the
governments of the United States and Bangladesh, the reports
noted.
</P>
<P>
The projects will be undertaken only with the concurrence of
the two governments and each individual project taken up will have
a separate MOU, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
