<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador Ready to Meet Congressmen, Says Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing
is ready to meet with U.S. Congressmen for face-to-face dialogue
on equal basis, said a Chinese diplomat here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li would like to have exchange with American
lawmakers on Capitol Hill, in the Chinese Embassy or even at his
residence to address mutual concerns and promote mutual
understanding, Counselor Zhang Keyuan told a press conference held
at the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
He, along with two other Chinese diplomats, were responding to
complaints made by Christopher Smith, chairman of the House
Subcommittee on International Operations and Human Rights, about
Ambassador Li's absence from a scheduled meeting on human rights
in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ambassador initially agreed to participate in the
meeting. However, the meeting notice was announced as "hearing," a
term unacceptable to a formal representative from a sovereign
country.
</P>
<P>
Smith denied that neither his nor the Subcommittee's employee
had used the word. But the Chinese Embassy officials showed to
the reporters evidences which prompted the ambassador to change
his mind Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Things were made difficult for Ambassador Li to have the
scheduled dialogue with the Congressmen," said Hu Mingwu, the
Embassy counselor for Congressional liaison.
</P>
<P>
The Embassy issued a statement Tuesday evening, announcing that
Ambassador Li had agreed to a face-to-face dialogue on equal basis
with members of the Subcommittee on the issue of human rights.
</P>
<P>
"Regrettably, in keeping with general diplomatic practice, it
is not appropriate for the Ambassador to appear as a witness
before the congressional subcommittee," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Smith said that he was informed that Ambassador Li would not
show up because the ground rules were broken only half an hour
before the event was scheduled. But Embassy Press Counselor Yu
Shuning said that it was not accurate and the embassy statement
was sent out Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Asked if a meeting could be arranged with Congressmen in the
days to come, Counselor Huo Mingwu said Ambassador Li has met with
60 Congressmen since he took up his post in Washington in
mid-March, and he is ready to meet more of them.
</P>
<P>
"The ambassador has good tea to entertain them here in the
Embassy or at his residence for a real dialogue not for TV show,
and we have nothing to hide and nothing to fear," said Counselor
Zhang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
