<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Increase Technical Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) will increase technical assistance for health projects in
China by 1.5 million US dollars over the next two years, today's
"China Daily" quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Including the new funding, the country is expected to receive a
total of 14 million US dollars in technical support from the WHO
for 1998-99, the WHO's China office said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to support the improvement of primary
and community health care, in addition to sponsoring training
programmes for health administrators and medical workers.
</P>
<P>
There will also be co-operation in promoting safe blood and
blood products, traditional medicine, maternal and child health
and food safety.
</P>
<P>
The additional technical assistance is targeted mainly at poor
and rural areas of China, said Dr R.W.K. Gee, the WHO
representative in China.
</P>
<P>
Rural doctors in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region will receive
training to upgrade services. Malaria control and anti-smoking
schemes will be launched in the provinces of Yunnan and Hainan.
</P>
<P>
Work will be carried out in Hunan Province and the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region to prevent HIV/AIDS and
sexually-transmitted diseases and to build health education
schools.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the WHO Western Pacific Office and the Chinese
Ministry of Health met last week in Manila, the Philippines, to
review previous collaborations and discuss future plans.
</P>
<P>
This annual meeting- a high-level contact on health issues-was
launched in 1979. Its aim is to solve major problems in
implementing WHO-China co-operative projects and determine new
plans.
</P>
<P>
Dr, S.T. Han, WHO regional director of the Western Pacific area,
said he believed such conferences provide a very good opportunity
to look at how the two sides can best work together and ensure
that the WHO's limited resources are used with maximum efficiency
supporting priority health concerns in China.
</P>
<P>
The WHO, established in 1948, is the UN's largest special
agency. China was one of the initiators of the organization, which
currently has 191 member states.
</P>
<P>
China and the WHO resumed co-operation in 1972. Since then the
WHO has awarded scholarships to more than 1,400 Chinese medical
workers, granted 100 million US dollars in technical assistance,
and helped set up 68 WHO/China collaboration centres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
