<HEADLINE> Lin Ti-Chuan Remains Carried to Beijing by Hearse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The remains of Lin Ti-chuan of
Taiwan are being transported from the Central Hospital of Haicheng
City in northeast China's Liaoning Province to Beijing in a hearse
provided by the Beijing-based Babaoshan Mortuary.
</P>
<P>
The hearse began its journey to Beijing around 6:00 a.m. this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Lin's younger brother and sister-in-law are accompanying the
hearse to Beijing in a car provided by the Haicheng city
government.
</P>
<P>
Lin's remains will undergo preliminary treatment in Beijing
before being transported to Hong Kong aboard Air China flight
CA101 on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Lin's remains are scheduled to be returned to Kaohsiung, Taiwan
at 4:45 p.m. the same day on a China Airlines flight, accompanied
by her family members.
</P>
<P>
Lin Ti-chuan was taken into custody unlawfully and subsequently
died in Haicheng City on July 29. Her death was apparently
connected to an economic dispute.
</P>
<P>
The departments concerned have actively helped Lin's family
members in dealing with the aftermath of her death.
</P>
<P>
Before Lin's family members arrived in Haicheng, the Taiwanese
Affairs Office of the Liaoning Provincial Government contacted
with the Beijing Babaoshan International Remains Transportation
Department on arrangements and costs involved in transporting the
remains via the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Straits. During the consultation, the Taiwanese Affairs Office of
the province learned that the family might ask to have Lin's
remains returned to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen in Haicheng City donated 85,000 yuan (10,240
U.S. dollars) on August 2 to defray the cost of returning Lin's
remains back to Taiwan for her parents.
</P>
<P>
While in Haicheng, Lin's relatives and friends took part in
traditional Taiwanese religious services to mourn for Lin
Ti-chuan, with help and special permission from the local
government.
</P>
<P>
Lin's parents and other family members are expected to arrive
in Beijing from Shenyang by air this afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
