<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Public Debts Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy's public debts have been
increasing, the Italian central bank reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, public debts had totaled 2,389 trillion
lire (1,357 billion U.S. dollars), 31 trillion lire (17.6 billion
dollars) more than that of the same period of 1997, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months of this year, Italy's total public
debts had increased by about 350 trillion lire (198.8 billion
dollars) compared with the end of last year, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
Italy's public debts have maintained at a high level for
years. It accounted for 121.6 percent of the country's gross
domestic products (GDP) by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government planned to reduce public debts to 118.5 percent
of GDP by the end of this year and 106.6 percent by the year of
2001, still far from the 60 percent target set by the European
Monetary Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
