<HEADLINE> Italy Registers a 1.8 Percent Inflation Rate in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices in Italy were stable
in July, leaving the yearly inflation rate at 1.8 percent, the
national statistics bureau Istat said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This confirmed the data from 11 sample cities issued at the end
of July, and was 0.1 percent lower than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
Istat said the average inflation rate over the past 12 months
was up 1.6 percent over the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The data showed that the biggest monthly price rises were for
health goods and services, especially medicines (up 0.7 percent),
while the prices of clothing, footwear, furniture, transport,
education and domestic services remained stable.
</P>
<P>
Housing and other accommodation prices dropped 0.2 percent, as
did water, electricity and energy prices.
</P>
<P>
Hotel, restaurant and bar prices fell 0.1 percent, along with
the prices of foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
But over the year, the biggest price rises were for health
goods and services, up three percent, followed by clothing,
footwear, entertainment and cultural events, which rose 2.7
percent, and accommodation, water, electricity and energy prices,
which increased 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cities where prices increased most in July were Florence,
Milan, Reggio Calabria, Genoa, Naples and Palermo, all with a 0.1
percent rise.
</P>
<P>
But prices fell 0.1 percent in Trieste, Venice, Cagliari,
Ancona, Potenza and Bari. Rome had the biggest fall, with prices
dropping 0.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks in Thailand Offered 5-Year Guarantee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand, the
country's central bank, has agreed to offer foreign banks that
take a major stake in Thai financial institutions a five-year
guarantee on their investments.
</P>
<P>
Kitti Patpongpibul, deputy governor of the central bank, was
quoted by Thursday's Bangkok Post as saying the guarantee would
help draw badly needed foreign capital for banks and finance
companies.
</P>
<P>
Essentially, the central bank is proposing to buy back the
shares at the same price originally paid by the foreign strategic
partners, at any point during the first five years of their
involvement with the local banks and finance institutions.
</P>
<P>
Details are yet to be worked out and the offer would also be
extended to foreign banks that have already made deals locally,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kitti, numerous foreign institutions were
interested in local banks, but were not sure of the market and
economic risks.
</P>
<P>
Thai financial institutions are under great pressure to raise
new capital to account for declining asset quality and the need
for higher provisions.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans are estimated at up to 35 percent of the 5
trillion baht (125 billion U.S. dollars) in total credit
outstanding. The sector needs at least 20 billion dollars in new
capital over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
Until now, only three local banks -- Bangkok Bank, Thai Farmers
Bank and Thai Danu Bank -- have successfully completed
recapitalization while the Bank of Asia expects to receive payment
for its share sale to ABN-Amro by next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
