<HEADLINE> Demand for Petroleum Products Declines in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Demand for petroleum products in
Thailand fell by 8.4 percent in the first half of this year
compared with the same period last year, to an average of 881,240
barrels per day, excluding supplies to petrochemical industries.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Petroleum Authority of
Thailand available Thursday, consumption of refined products
slipped by 11.4 percent to 673,950 barrels per day while use of
natural gas in place of fuel oil rose by 3.1 percent to the
equivalent of 207,290 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum purchases from local and imported sources combined
dipped by 8.3 percent to just more than 1 million barrels per day.
Total imports declined by 10.9 percent to 735,090 barrels. Imports
of crude fell 6.3 percent and finished products 59.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Demand for finished products also fell: diesel oil by 17.4
percent, fuel oil by 10.7 percent, gasoline by 3 percent, jet fuel
by 5.3 percent, cooking gas by 3 percent, kerosene by 35.4
percent, bitumen by 18.8 percent and lubricants by 22.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
