<HEADLINE> WNBA Players Opt for Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A majority of WNBA players
agreed to form a union and have selected the embattled NBA Players
Assocation (NBPA) to represent them.
</P>
<P>
The NBPA already has presented WNBA officials with a request to
begin formal negotiations, said NBPA executive director Billy
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we've received signed union cards from close to 100 of
the 120 WNBA players since our organizing drive began about four
weeks ago," he noted, "It presents us with a clear mandate to
begin negotiating with a WNBA on behalf of these players and we
are delighted to have the opportunity to do so."
</P>
<P>
Hunter and the NBPA have done little negotiating with the NBA
since the league imposed a lockout on June 30th. He will join
other union representatives Thursday in New York for face-to-face
talks with NBA officials. The meeting will be the first between
the sides since the players association filed an unfair practice
charge with the National Labor Relations Board, claiming the
lockout is illegal.
</P>
<P>
"This union will be driven by the players' agenda, above all
else," Hunter said, referring to the WNBA entity.
</P>
<P>
Agent Bruce Levy, who represents more than 30 WNBA
players,said:"We are very pleased that the WNBA is as successful
as it has been, and we feel that the time has come to ensure that
the players receive their fair share of the benefits that derive
from the success. The players have decisively concluded that the
NBPA is the organization that can convert that potential into
promise." 
</P>
</TEXT>
