<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Model Village (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A piece of saline-alkaline and
straw-scattered land here and there on the plains has been the
major property of the people of Hangmin Village for thousands of
years.
</P>
<P>
However, local villagers have put an end to such a life through
hard work over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
They have built multi-storey apartment buildings surrounded by
trees and flowers instead of straw. By the end of last year,
Hangmin Village in Xiaoshan City in east China's Zhejiang Province,
had established 18 joint and cooperative industrial and commercial
enterprises and firms funded by the village itself, and three
farms.
</P>
<P>
The village, with a population of 1,067, now boasts total
assets of 770 million yuan (92.77 million U.S. dollars) in
industrial sales, and the annual per capita income of local people
was nearly 10,000 yuan (1,205 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The per capita income for local villagers was only 148 yuan
(17.83 U.S .dollars) only 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, the village set up its first enterprise -- a bleaching
and dyeing plant. In 1982, net profits of the plant exceeded 1
million yuan (120,400 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hangmin people made a wise choice and invested the money in
expanding production in order to realize even greater profits.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Chongqing, board chairman of the Hangmin Industrial Group,
said his group is now engaged in textiles, printing and dyeing,
chemicals and electricity, as well as hotels, department stores
and real estate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Marks 53rd Anniversary of Atomic Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hiroshima on Thursday commemorated
the 53rd anniversary of the atomic bombing of the Japanese city,
with citizens praying for those who died from the blast.
</P>
<P>
Hiroshima citizens began arriving at the Peace Memorial Park
before dawn to offer prayers for those who died.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Hiroshima Mayor Takashi Hiraoka
and other dignitaries and representatives gathered at the park for
the Peace Memorial Ceremony, and laid flowers at the stone
cenotaph to the bomb victims.
</P>
<P>
At 8:15, the exact time of the blast, participants at the
ceremony offered one minute of silent prayer, while a bell
symbolizing peace sounded throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Hiraoka dedicated a new list of 4,927 names of atomic
bomb victims who have died since August 6 last year, bringing the
total number of deaths to 207,045.
</P>
<P>
Hiraoka delivered a peace declaration, urging the international
community to start immediate negotiations on a treaty to ban the
use of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"All countries should immediately initiate negotiations on a
treaty for the non-use of nuclear weapons as one step on the road
to these (nuclear) weapons' total abolition," he said.
</P>
<P>
Following a peace pledge delivered by primary school children,
1,500 doves, the symbol of peace, were released into the sky.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely deplorable that India and Pakistan conducted
nuclear tests in May this year," Obuchi said in his speech.
</P>
<P>
"Our government strongly urges both the Indian and Pakistani
governments to immediately stop nuclear tests and unconditionally
conclude the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, to stop the
development of nuclear weapons and their transportation means
which are missiles, and to unconditionally conclude the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also vowed that Japan would continue to stick to and
strengthen the nuclear non-proliferation system, and make further
progress on nuclear weapon states' nuclear disarmament. He said he
believeed this to be Japan's utmost mission.
</P>
<P>
The atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima in southwest Japan on
August 6, 1945, by a United States B-29 bomber Enola Gay. An
estimated 140,000 people had died in the world's first nuclear
attack by the end of that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
