<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Forecasts Oil Price Fall in Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The prices of Venezuelan oil will
continue to drop in the international market and will remain below
13 U.S. dollars per barrel for the next three years, the
state-owned petroleum company, PDVSA, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The company predicts that the country's oil production ceiling
would be 6.2 million barrels per day for the year 2006 and 5.8
million barrels for 2008.
</P>
<P>
The company attributed the price declines to the Asian
financial crisis, the return of Iraq to the international oil
market and the warmest winter in the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
The average price of Venezuelan oil could reach 12.5 dollars
per barrel this year compared to 1997's 16.49 dollars per barrel,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, Mexico and Saudi Arabia signed an agreement in March
to reduce their production each by 200,000 and 300,000 barrels per
day to cope with the oil price crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
