<HEADLINE> Thailand Goes On-Line to Promote Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Export
Promotion in Thailand is staging trade exhibitions on the Internet
as a new way to publicize Thai products to the world market, The
Bangkok Post said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, gems and jewelry will be the first
sector featured, with extensive previews of the Bangkok Gems and
Jewelry Fair, scheduled for September 9-12.
</P>
<P>
The department has invested 600,000 baht (15,000 U.S. dollars)
to develop the new Web site: .
</P>
<P>
Director-General Sanit Vorapanya of the department said that
more than 50 million people use the Internet worldwide and that
many have high purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cost of organizing an on-line trade show, which
would be available 24 hours a day, is much lower than for a live
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Sanit said Thai exporters should improve their knowledge of
information technology since the Internet is becoming many
consumers' primary source of information.
</P>
<P>
The next sector to be featured on the site would be leather
goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Komson Opassathavorn, president of the Thai Gem and
Jewellry Traders Association, applauded the project, saying all
400 members of the association have participated in the project.
</P>
<P>
Exporters might also develop their own site soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism about the effectiveness of the promotion,
particularly in the United States, Thailand's largest market for
gems and jewellry exports, since 70 percent of the world's
Internet users live in that country. 
</P>
