<HEADLINE> Chinese City Protect Historical Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Yongzhou city government
in central China's Hunan Province has made an effort to protect its
historical relics in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The city has 1,700 historical sites and nearly 10,000 relics,
including China's oldest glass object, from the Han Dynasty (206
B.C.--220) and the rare golden phoenix coronet of the Tang Dynasty
(618--907).
</P>
<P>
To better protect the relics, the city has spent 10 million
yuan building a central storehouse and a 7,000-sq.m. museum. It
has also spent 30 million yuan on a major historical relics
protection project, repairing ancient buildings like the Liuzi
Temple and the Huilong Pagoda, and removing 10,000 sq.m. of
illegal residential or office buildings from the historical sites.
</P>
<P>
It has collected 1,000 ethnic relics from the Yao ethnic
minority for research and display. 
</P>
</TEXT>
