<HEADLINE> Manila May Ease Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Buoyed by a decline in the
inflation rate last month, the monetary authorities have vowed to
adopt certain leniency in the management of the country's monetary
policy to stimulate economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Manila Bulletin Thursday quoted Central Bank Governor Gabriel
Singson as saying the July inflation rate had bolstered the
likelihood that the average inflation rate can be kept to
single-digit this year.
</P>
<P>
The government announced Wednesday a 10.6-percent year-on-year
inflation in July, down from 10.7 percent the previous month,
bringing the average inflation for the first seven months to 9.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Singson said an indication that inflation had reached its peak
was the month-on-month change rate of only 0.3 percent in July
compared to the 1.7 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent change of tack, Singson declared Wednesday that
"greater flexibility" in monetary growth may be assured because of
the more favorable prospects in inflation.
</P>
<P>
This stance is a reversal of its previous tack of prudent
monetary management which has characterized the monetary policy in
the past year since the regional currency crisis hit the
Philippines seriously.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the strong resolve of the monetary authorities to
relax their grip on monetary management was bolstered not only by
the reduction in the inflation rate but also by the
overperformance in the level of the central bank's net
international reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
