<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned Over Congo's Deteriorating Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Wednesday
urged neighbors of the Democratic Republic of Congo not to
involved in widening the country's revolt against President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is concerned by reports that Rwandan troops are
involved in military operations ... in support of a Congolese
military rebellion against President Kabila," State Department
spokesman James Foley said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
"We urge all countries in the region to respect the territorial
integrity of the Congo, refrain from becoming involved in the
conflict and respect international law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Congo was reported to be deteriorating as
revolt against President Kabila deepened on Wednesday with his
foreign minister defecting to the rebels and fighting was reported
in the country's third city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Foley said the United States was concerned over the
deteriorating security situation there and especially by instances
of the arrest and harassment of Congolese citizens of ethnic Tutsi
origin.
</P>
<P>
The White House said on Tuesday that Washington was in touch
with regional African countries to assess what was going on in
Congo and how to prevent the conflict from widening. And African
leaders planned to meet in Zimbabwe on Friday to discuss the
revolt, which President Kabila blamed on estranged ally Rwanda and
members of Congo's ethnic Tutsi Banyamulenge community.
</P>
<P>
The State Department has ordered all nonessential U.S. embassy
workers to leave Congo and warned U.S. citizens against traveling
to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
