<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Urged to Keep Prudency in Dispute With Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican politicians have
urged their government to be prudent in handling a dispute with
neighboring Nicaragua over right of navigation on the San Juan
border river between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We should not nourish polemics that concern only to
Nicaraguans," the former government vice minister Jose Manuel
Gutierrez said wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Another former government vice minister, Fernando Naranjo, said
that the matter should be handled very carefully and with no
prejudices.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican President Miguel Angel Rodriguez said on Wednesday
that he expects to give a big hug to Nicaraguan President Arnoldo
Aleman when they meet in Colombia next Friday, according to media
reports here.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant treaties, the 300-kilometer section of the river
that separates Costa Rica from Nicaragua is under Nicaragua's
sovereignty. Costa Rica has the right of free navigation through
this waterway. However, the treaties have not specified whether
the navigation right covers armed Costa Rican officers patroling
the river.
</P>
<P>
The latest dispute between the two countries flared up almost a
month ago when Nicaraguan authorities prohibited members of the
Costa Rican Public Force to circulate around with weapons.
</P>
<P>
Despite the signing of an agreement last week by the Ministry
of Public Security of Costa Rica and the Nicaraguan Ministry of
Defense, the dispute has relapsed.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Nicaragua suspended free navigation following a
heavy deployment of military personnel by Costa Rica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
