<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Military Atlases Found in Sichuan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 6 (Xinhua)-- Two Japanese military atlases, the
"Pocket Atlas of China" and the "Pocket Atlas of Manchuria" have
been found here, providing new evidence of Japanese militarists'
aggressive ambitions for China during World War II, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The "Pocket Atlas of China" was issued by a publishing house in
Tokyo on June 20, 1941, according to its back cover. It includes
13 maps, each 14.5 centimeters (cm) long and 8 cm wide.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan and northeast China's three provinces -- Heilongjiang,
Jilin and Liaoning -- are not included on any maps in the atlas.
</P>
<P>
The same-sized "Pocket Atlas of Manchuria" with eight maps, was
issued on Oct. 5, 1940, by the same publishing house. It divided
the three northeast provinces into 19 "provinces" with the
"capital" marked in Xinjing, now called Changchun in Jilin
Province.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time an "Atlas of Manchuria" has been found in
China, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The two atlases are now in the possession of Li Jinxing,
director of the Automatic-control Meters Plant in Wenjiang
County, Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Li happened to find the atlases as he was packaging his
father's books.
</P>
<P>
He said that his father seized these two atlases in 1945 from
Japanese soldiers in a battle in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Early this June, a similar military atlas was found in Liaoning
Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
