<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- A total of seven bodies have been recovered from the
rubble of a collapsed apartment house in Berlin until Wednesday
evening after a suspected gas explosion destroyed the house early
Tuesday morning, German rescue workers said.
</P>
<P>
The seven dead were all those who were reported missing after
the four-storey apartment house in a western district of Berlin
collapsed at about 6:00 a.m. Tuesday after a huge explosion,
officials said. (BC-Germany-Explosion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- A German official Wednesday dismissed U.S. accusations
that the Bonn government was forcing back Bosnian refugees living
in the country for political considerations ahead of Germany's
general elections in September this year.
</P>
<P>
The return of Bosnian war refugees living in Germany was
running according to plan and had in no way been speeded up, said
Germany's envoy for Bosnian refugee affair, Dietmar Schlee,
Wednesday in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Of the 85,000 Bosnian refugees who left Germany in the first
seven months of this year, only about 1,200 had been expelled,
Schlee said. "There are no mass expulsions," he
added. (Germany-US-Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The first terrorist prisoners in Northern Ireland
could be freed from jail by the end of this month, officials said
in the provincial capital Belfast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sentence Review Commissioners, appointed to implement the
legislation, said they would issue application forms to eligible
prisoners Thursday. Reviewing them could take less than a month.
</P>
<P>
"It is conceivable that there could be a few prisoners going
free by the end of August or the beginning of September," an
official said. (UK-N.Ireland-Prisoner)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Contact has been re-established with the
one-billion-dollar Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO)
satellite following six weeks of silence.
</P>
<P>
Signals sent from a station in Canberra, Australia, were
answered by SOHO in the form of intermittent bursts of signal
lasting from two to 10 seconds and do not contain any data
information.
</P>
<P>
However, "they show that the spacecraft is still capable of
receiving and responding to ground commands," according to a press
release from the European Space Agency (ESA). (UK-Lost Satellite)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Wednesday that it was
waiting to assess Iraq's actions after its parliament voted to
freeze U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's national Assembly voted unanimously to suspend
U.N. weapons inspections. The move has yet to be endorsed by Iraqs
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman P.J. Crowley said the vote by Iraq's
parliament amounted to "political rhetoric," and Washington would
"watch Iraqi actions, not their words." (US-Iraq-Weapons
Inspections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq announced Wednesday to suspend cooperation with
U.N. weapons inspectors until conditions it sets are met, a strong
effort believed designed to see the eight-year-old U.N. sanctions
on it lifted early.
</P>
<P>
President Saddam Hussein made the decision soon after a
parliament special session called on the Iraqi leaders to stop
cooperation with the U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said the president decided to
"immediately and completely suspend" cooperation with both the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq, known as UNSCOM, and
the International Atomic Energy Agency. (Iraq-UN 4th lead
Writethru)  
</P>
</TEXT>
