<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joblessness Soars in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in New Zealand
hit its highest level in four years in the second quarter of this
year and is expected to worsen as the economic recession takes its
toll, according to government statistics published Thursday by The
Dominion.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that the unemployment rate soared to 7.7
percent of the working population in the second quarter from 6.6
percent a year earlier. An estimated 143,000 were out of work
during the three months to June this year, including 79,000 men
and 64,000 women.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted New Zealand Employment
Minister Peter McCardle as saying the rise in unemployment "was
not unexpected" because of the Asian economic decline.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, Asia used to take a third of New
Zealand's exports.
</P>
<P>
McCardle said positive economic growth was expected through
next year, helped particularly by a lower New Zealand dollar,
lower interest rates and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion also quoted some economists as saying they
expected 163,000 to be jobless by next March, with the
unemployment rate peaking at 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
A rise to 8.5 percent would put New Zealand ahead of Australia
(8.2 percent), Britain (6.3 percent), the United States (4.5
percent) and Japan (4.3 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
