<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Super League at Horizon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A new European competition format
Super League is at the horizon after announcements from the
region's soccer governing body UEFA and top clubs Manchester
United, Arsenal and Ajax Amsterdam on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
UEFA, for the first time since reports of a proposed league
surfaced two weeks ago, said that it had its own projects for a
new competition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, such top clubs as two former European champions
Manchester United, Ajax and current English champions Arsenal also
admitted publicly for the first time they were involved in
discussion for a breakaway midweek competition.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Wednesday, UEFA spokesman Frits
Ahlstrom said:"The fact Manchester United made this announcement
today is not news for us. We have known all about United's
involvement for some time."
</P>
<P>
"But we have also been working on our own plans for a new
competition. We have a clear idea of how the competition should
be organised and I think they will be met very positively."
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes changes do not happen as fast as we would like, but
I think that our plans could be made public at the next UEFA
Executive Committee meeting in Lisbon on October 6."
</P>
<P>
"The keyword for us is the supporter. That is absolutely
crucial for UEFA. There is no point in having matches played in
empty stadiums, even for television and we have to make it right
for the supporter."
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, Manchester United confirmed in a
statement issued through the London Stock Exchange that they were
involved in talks concerning the Super League which would bring
together the top 16 clubs in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Ajax also admitted earlier that they had also been involved in
talks. Both Manchester United and Ajax also confirmed that they
were committed to remaining in their domestic leagues. Arsenal
issued a similar statement on the day.
</P>
<P>
Spanish clubs Barcelona and Real Madrid, Italian champions
Juventus, Inter Milan and AC Milan are all expected to make their
involvement public soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
