<HEADLINE> Plain-clothes Police to Act Against Cricket Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Plain-clothes police and video
surveillance will be used for the first time to prevent cricket
hooliganism at the fifth Test between England and South Africa at
Headingley.
</P>
<P>
The new techniques are similar to those used by their
colleagues in the National Football Intelligence Unit.
</P>
<P>
The match commander for police operations, Inspector David
Boyle, said there was "increasing evidence that people are
attending in order to extend their football xenophobia within
cricket".
</P>
<P>
"We have seen this in the wearing of football strips, the
football banners in the crowd and the organised chanting which has
been seen at cricket."
</P>
<P>
During the first Test at Edgbaston, more than 100 people were
ejected and there were complaints about the behaviour of people
drinking.
</P>
<P>
At the third Test in Old Trafford, drinking was banned for the
first time at a test match. People wearing dress which officials
considered offensive or hats, wigs and headdresses which could
block views were also barred.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to be killjoys," said Chris Hassell, the chief
executive of Yorkshire Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
"Fancy dress is perfectly acceptable so long as it is not
outrageous and does not block the view of people behind," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
