<HEADLINE> Annan to Stay for Briefing by Chief Arms Inspector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has postponed his travel plan for 24 hours in order to
participate in Thursday's Security Council consultations on Iraq,
his spokesman announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan will be present during the briefing by chief U.N. arms
inspector Richard Butler, who came back on Wednesday after his
talks with the Iraqi Government on Iraq's disarmament broke down
early this week.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced on Wednesday to suspend cooperation with U.N.
weapons inspectors until conditions it sets are met. The move was
seen as an effort for the early lifting of the eight-year U.N.
sanctions on Iraq, imposed since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who has been scheduled to go to Lisbon on Thursday to
attend the opening ceremony of the World Conference of Ministers
Responsible for Youth, said the Security Council will hear
Butler's briefing before taking further steps in arms inspection
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Declining to see the latest developments with Iraq as a crisis,
Butler said he has instructed his arms teams in Baghdad to
continue their normal work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
