<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Mystified by Iraq's Acton of Suspending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, executive
chairman of the United Nations Special Commission in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, said Wednesday he
was puzzled by Iraq's blunt action to suspend the arms talks when
resolution of several issues was near.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon returning to the Headquarters of the
United Nations in New York from Baghdad, Butler said that in the
areas of missiles and chemical weapons, U.N. inspectors were very
close to being able to declare that Iraq has complied with
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We were getting there. If it was a five-lap race, we were
halfway into the fifth lap. Why stop the race when you are getting
towards the finish line?" Butler said.
</P>
<P>
But Butler said that in the area of biological weapons, Iraq's
complying with U.N. resolutions was in bad shape, and a lot more
was needed.
</P>
<P>
"What is really sad about all this is that missiles and
chemical weapons were in pretty good shape. We need some more
evidence to close them down," he said.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Iraq had the power to escape the sweeping sanctions
imposed after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990 by proving to the
United Nations that it had destroyed all its prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who cut his visit to Iraq, will brief U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on his talks with Iraq's Deputy Prime
Minister Tareq Aziz which broke down Monday due to sharp
differences between them. He is scheduled to brief the Security
Council Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
