<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Reject Democrats' Plan on 2000 Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives voted on Wednesday against allowing statistical
sampling in the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
The Republican-controlled chamber rejected, 227-201, a
Democrats' proposal to keep the door open for sampling. The vote
ensured that the battle will continue into the fall or beyond,
because President Bill Clinton has threatened to veto the spending
bill containing census provisions. The Senate-approved version of
the measure sidesteps the issue.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and the Democrats want the Census Bureau, as it had
planned, to use sampling to help tally hard-to-reach Americans,
disproportionate numbers of whom are minorities who tend to vote
Democratic. Republicans argue that sampling is unreliable and
would let the Clinton administration manipulate the figures to
Democrats' advantage.
</P>
<P>
Census data, gathered every decade as required by the
Constitution, is used to redraw House district lines and to
distribute hundreds of billions in federal spending.
</P>
<P>
Republicans raised doubts about the admistration's
trustworthiness while Democrats accused Republicans of wanting to
undercount minorities.
</P>
<P>
After its 1990 head-count, the Census Bureau estimated that it
had fallen short of the actual population by about four million
people, or just below two percent. The bureau said unusually high
undercounts occurred among blacks, Hispanics, Asians and American
Indians.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a recurrence, the bureau has planned to use sampling.
Under the technique, workers would visit many homes whose
residents had failed to return census forms, and use that
information to extrapolate totals for each state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
