<HEADLINE> Rwanda Denies Involvement in Congo (K)'s Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Rwandan President
Posteur Bizimingu Wednesday reiterated that his country has not
been involved in the on-going fightings in the Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during an official meeting at the State House here
with his counterpart President Frederick Chiluba, Bizimingu
stressed that Rwanda has no reason to get involved and said it is
regrettable development that this region gets involved in a lot
of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being there is no particular reason for Rwanda
to be involved in the internal situation of Congo (Kinshasa),"
said Bizimingu.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan president, accompanied by the First Lady and four
cabinet ministers, arrived in Zambia Wednesday morning for a
three-day state visit.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in Kinshasa Tuesday accused its former ally Rwanda
of invading the country and called on the U.N Security Council to
order an immediate retreat of the troops that invaded its
territory.
</P>
<P>
And on Monday, Congoleses President Laurent Kabila's
government urged its neighbors to resist the temptation to
involve themselves in an army rebellion in the east of the
republic. The rebellion followed Kabila's order to send Rwandan
soldiers back to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
In a clear reference to the soldiers from the Rwandan
Patriotic Army which helped Kabila to oust late dictator Muboto
Sese Seko last year, Presidential Affairs Minister Pierre Victor
Mpoyo charged on the state television that the rebellion has been
planned for some time by foreign officers who were ordered home
last week. 
</P>
