<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Affects U.S. Manufacturing and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Asian crisis is taking a
toll on the U.S. manufacturers and farmers, but strong domestic
consumer demand is contributing to push the overall economic
growth, the Federal Reserve reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Fed report found widespread evidence that Asia's troubles
were cutting into demand for the U.S manufactured goods and
depressing the prices of many farm commodities.
</P>
<P>
But even with these adverse effects, the 12 Fed districts
"generally indicate a high level of economic activity," the
central bank said in its latest snapshot of economic conditions
around the country.
</P>
<P>
The latest report said that economic activity had been
depressed in the second quarter, not only by Asia but also by the
U.S. No. 1 auto-maker--- the GM's strike, which was settled last
week.
</P>
<P>
It said the Atlanta, Chicago, Richmond, New York and St. Louis
districts had all reported declines in manufacturing employment
due to the GM strike with Asia's impact widespread as well.
</P>
<P>
"Weakness in Asia and increased low-cost imports (from that
region) continued to depress activity for a variety of U.S.
products," the Fed survey found. "Manufacturers reported that
sales and orders for apparel and textiles, computing equipment,
electronic components, industrial machinery, paper and wood
products fell in many districts."
</P>
<P>
The Asian impact on the farm sector has been evident in falling
prices for many crops as recessions in many nations in that part
of the world have contributed to lower demand.
</P>
<P>
"Price declines for some commodities have been so large that
producers cannot cover costs," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Adding to farmers' troubles from Asia, the Fed noted severe
droughts across the South that destroyed crops and damaged pasture
land for cattle.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Fed reported that consumer demand has remained
strong and low mortgage rates have contributed to a boom in
housing sales and construction.
</P>
<P>
The latest economic report seemed to underscore worries on the
inflation front, noting that all regions of the country were
reporting tight labor markets.
</P>
<P>
"Labor shortages were broad-based and some skilled workers were
in especially short supply," the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts believe that stable inflation so far this year
will allow the Fed to remain the interest rate on hold until more
is known about the Asian crisis impact on the U.S. economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
