<HEADLINE> Arab League Hopes Talks End War in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cairo-based Arab League
Secretariat expressed the hope Wednesday that current peace
negotiations between Khartoum and opposition factions would
realize peace and put an end to Sudan's 15-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat said in a statement that it is closely
following up the ongoing peace negotiations between the government
and southern rebels in the Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa under
the Intergovernmental Authority for Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
The Arab forum underlined its stance calling for maintaining
the unity of Sudan and asked all parties to respond to appeals by
the international community to stop fighting so that humanitarian
aid can reach the regions affected by the war in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, during the current round of talks, which began
on Tuesday and are expected to end Thursday, have reportedly
agreed to discuss details of an internationally supervised vote on
self-determination for the south.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) has been fighting for
autonomy of the south from the north since 1983. Fightings
combined with perennial famines have claimed more than 1.5 million
lives.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the two sides declared a three-month ceasefire in
the southwestern famine-stricken Bahr al-Ghazal province to
expedite delivery of relief food. On the eve of the talks, Sudan
expanded its cease-fire areas, which rebuffed by the SPLA as a
publicity stint. 
</P>
</TEXT>
