<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Posts Better Economic Trend Than EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The 11-country euro zone
registered a better economic development trend than the 15-nation
European Union in July, the European Commission said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The trend was reported as a result of the business and consumer
survey conducted by the commission's Directorate General for
economic and financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
Economic sentiment in both the euro zone and the European Union
improved in July compared with a month earlier. The euro zone saw
an increase of 0.7 percent while the union had an increase of 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The consumer confidence increased in the euro zone whereas it
remained stable in the EU as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France both posted marked improvement in the
consumer's confidence indicator each with a 4-percentage-point
increase.
</P>
<P>
The euro zone includes Belgium, Germany, France, Italy,
Ireland, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Austria, Finland, Spain and
Portugal. EU member states Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece
did not join the single currency mechanism that is scheduled to be
inaugurated next January.  
</P>
</TEXT>
