<HEADLINE> Moldova, Gazprom Start Talks on Gas Debt Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The government of Moldova and
Russia's oil and gas giant Gazprom began talks Wednesday on
Kishinev's debts to gas supplies.
</P>
<P>
The discussions will focus on the rescheduling of the debt of
more than 300 million U.S. dollars, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Most of the debt is owed by the Dniester region, which provides
power supply to the whole former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
Moldova is considering offering Gazprom another package of
bonds worth 80-90 million U.S. dollars at an annual interest rate
of 7.5 percent, and shares in a joint venture to be created with
Gazprom, Vice Prime Minister Ion Sturza said following his talks
with Gazprom in Moscow last July.
</P>
<P>
However, Sturza said, the creation of the joint venture could
be complicated by the Dniester region's demand for a debt amnesty
in exchange for the unhindered removal of Russian weapons and
property from its territory.
</P>
<P>
The former 14th Russian army was stationed in Dniester.
</P>
<P>
Moldova consumes an annual 3 billion cubic meters of Russian
gas and about 40 percent goes to the Dniester power plant.
</P>
<P>
It had already transferred 140 million U.S. dollars worth of
bonds to Gazprom in 1997 for seven years at 7.5 percent per annum
as debt payments, Tass said.  
</P>
