<HEADLINE> German Economic Growth Sets to Continue, Institute Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The economic upswing in Germany
would continue at least until 1999 and is expected to have
positive impact on the job market, the German Ifo economic
research institute predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest economic forecast issued by the
Munich-based institute on Wednesday, Germany is expected to see an
economic growth of 2.7 percent this year and 2.5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"If the framework conditions are improved further, the upswing
could continue for a long time," said Ifo's chief economist, Willi
Leibfritz.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the sustained economic growth, Germany's jobless
total was expected to be cut by 575,000 to around four million by
the end of 1999, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
The Ifo institute on Wednesday also viewed the continuing Asian
financial crisis as a risk factor for Germany's economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
"Without the Asian crisis we would probably see an economic
growth of three percent," Leibfritz said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Ifo economist did not see any negative impact on
the German economy from the single European currency, the euro,
which is due to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"At least in the first year the euro will be a strong baby," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
