<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16% Ugandan Babies Borne to HIV-Positive Mothers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- About 16 percent of the new-born
babies in Uganda are those whose mothers are proved to be
HIV-positive, a Ugandan AIDS Commission official told Xinhua here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Anne Nakaweesi, the administration and advocacy coordinator with
the organization, said that at present, out of 1,000 live births,
some 163 babies are borne to HIV positive mothers.
</P>
<P>
Children borne to HIV positive mothers face deprivation,
stigmatization and discrimination, she added.
</P>
<P>
Since most of the parents suffering AIDS die at an earlier
age, their children are forced to take the heavy burden of the
family by taking care of the younger siblings, leading to
creation of children-headed households.
</P>
<P>
The orphaned children are prone to be exposed to sexual abuse,
harassment and sometimes loss of property.
</P>
<P>
The children are too young to protect their property after the
death of the HIV positive parents. Their properties are often
taken away of other members of the big family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
