<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Suspends Cooperation With U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced Wednesday to
suspend cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors until conditions
it sets are met, a strong effort believed designed to see the
eight-year-old U.N. sanctions on it lifted early.
</P>
<P>
President Saddam Hussein made the decision soon after a
parliament special session called on the Iraqi leaders to stop
cooperation with the U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a joint meeting of the powerful
Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling Baath Party chaired
by Saddam.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said the president decided to
"immediately and completely suspend" cooperation with both the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq, known as UNSCOM, and
the International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
One of the conditions set is the recomposition of UNSCOM. Iraq
demands equal representation of the member states of the Security
Council on the Special Commission, and Iraq's participation in
UNSCOM work as an observer.
</P>
<P>
Another one is to move UNSCOM headquarters to Geneva from New
York with an aim to keep the Commission away from the U.S. direct
influence.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also asks for a rotation of UNSCOM chairmanship among the
five permanent members of the Security Council, which means Iraq
wants the removal of UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler from his
position.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused UNSCOM and Butler as U.S. stooges in Washington's
drive to intentionally prolong the sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Iraq reiterates that it has fulfilled all its
obligations toward relevant U.N. resolutions and that all its
prohibited weapons have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The statement accuses UNSCOM of being dishonest and unfair when
handling disarmament issues in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It also calls on the United Nations to respect Iraq's
sovereignty and legitimate rights, saying it reserves the right to
dispel any weapons inspector violating such rights.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made when Iraq has repeated several times that
the sanctions must be lifted in the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, the sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait can only be lifted when U.N. inspectors verify that the
country is free of chemical, biological weapons and long-range
missiles.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of UNSCOM-Iraq talks on the issue collapsed
last Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
