<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malfunctioning SOHO Satellite Contacted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Contact has been re-established
with the one-billion-dollar Solar and Heliospheric Observatory
(SOHO) satellite following six weeks of silence.
</P>
<P>
Signals sent from a station in Canberra, Australia, were
answered by SOHO in the form of intermittent bursts of signal
lasting from two to 10 seconds and do not contain any data
information.
</P>
<P>
However, "they show that the spacecraft is still capable of
receiving and responding to ground commands," according to a press
release from the European Space Agency (ESA).
</P>
<P>
The ESA said that the slow process of regaining control of SOHO
and restoring it to an operational attitude will start
immediately, with attempts to initiate data transmissions in order
to perform an initial assessment of the spacecraft on-board
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Radio contact with SOHO, a joint mission of the ESA and the
U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), was
interrupted on 25 June.
</P>
<P>
Last week, radio telescopes on Earth detected the SOHO
satellite, which is found apparently rotating slowly near to its
monitoring point in space and seems to have suffered only minimal
damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
