<HEADLINE> Nile Flooding Displaces 20,000 in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Flood waters from River Nile
caused by recent heavy rains have displaced some 20,000 people
over a wide area in Northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The rotten vegetation resulted from last year's torrential
rains brought about by the El Nino weather pattern and the washed
away shoreline have formed a huge blockage of the river, Radio
Uganda reported Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Earth and rocks have moved down stream, causing blockage and
flooding in Apac District, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The flooded junction is situated where the river flows out of
Lake Kwania about 200 kms from the source of the Nile at Lake
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
The combination of vegetation and land mass is reported to
cover an area of more than 96 square kms.
</P>
<P>
According to Action Aid Emergency Officer Amanya Ebye, the
floodwater, worsened by recent rains, has moved two kms inland in
some places, covering grazing and farmlands and submerging whole
villages.
</P>
<P>
As a result, fishermen along the river have recorded lower
catches and trade is at a standstill because of impassable roads.
There is increased incidence of cholera in the area.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the long term effects of the flooding could
include famine and more human migration from the affected area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
