<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2040 GMT, August 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two Jewish settlers were killed in the West Bank
early Wednesday in an attack launched by suspected Palestinian
militants, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The attack happened in the Jewish settlement of Itzhar,
about 10 kilometers away from the Palestinian West Bank city
of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
The two young men, only one of whom was armed, were shot when
they were on a routine security patrol of the settlement
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
Suspected Palestinian militants fired at the settlers from a
close range, and escaped after taking away their guns
after confirming they were dead. (Israel-Settlers-Killing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Following the collapse of its talks with the
U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, Iraq
has vowed to take measures to end the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after an emergency meeting of the
powerful Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling Baath Party
chaired by President Saddam Hussein late Tuesday night, the Iraqi
government blamed the UNSCOM for the failure of the latest round
of talks that broke down Monday night. (Iraq-UN-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Wednesday urged the United States to publicize its peace plan as
soon as possible in order to save the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made this request in a statement before presenting his
new cabinet lineups to the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC).
(Arafat-Israeli Withdrawal-US Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Iraq has asked for upgrading diplomatic relations with
Egypt and reopening embassies in both Cairo and Baghdad after
seven years of icy ties, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Sherif Reehan, head of the Egyptian Interest Section in
Baghdad, told the Egyptian news agency from Baghdad Wednesday that
the request came at a recent meeting between him and Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz. (Egypt-Iraq-Diplomacy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Wednesday present
his new cabinet lineup to the Palestinian Legislative Council
(PLC) and pledged "accountability and transparency" in all
government institutions.
</P>
<P>
Although some new ministers are added to the list, Arafat made
no major changes in the reshuffle and most of the former key
cabinet members retained their presence in the new mix.
(Palestine-Cabinet Reshuffle 2nd Lead-Writethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq announced Wednesday to suspend cooperation with
U.N. weapons inspectors until conditions it sets are met, a strong
effort believed designed to see the eight-year-old U.N. sanctions
on it lifted early.
</P>
<P>
President Saddam Hussein made the decision soon after a
parliament special session called on the Iraqi leaders to stop
cooperation with the U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a joint meeting of the powerful
Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling Baath Party chaired
by Saddam.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said the president decided to
"immediately and completely suspend" cooperation with both the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq, known as UNSCOM, and
the International Atomic Energy Agency. (Iraq-UN 4th lead
Writethru)  
</P>
</TEXT>
