<HEADLINE> N.Irish Prisoner to Be Released Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The first terrorist prisoners in
Northern Ireland could be freed from jail by the end of this
month, officials said in the provincial capital Belfast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sentence Review Commissioners, appointed to implement the
legislation, said they would issue application forms to eligible
prisoners Thursday. Reviewing them could take less than a month.
</P>
<P>
"It is conceivable that there could be a few prisoners going
free by the end of August or the beginning of September," an
official said.
</P>
<P>
Between 400 and 420 jailed members of rival Protestant and
Catholic guerrilla groups now observing cease-fires are set for
early release within the next two years under the peace agreement
reached last April.
</P>
<P>
Those to be released include members of the Irish Republican
Army, which had fought for years to end British rule in Northern
Ireland, and the pro-British Ulster Defense Association and Ulster
Volunteer Force.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla groups that have continued bombings and shootings
-- the extremist pro-British Loyalist Volunteer Force and a trio
of republican splitter groups -- will not be included in the
scheme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
