<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First World Conference of Ministers Responsible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The challenges and
opportunities facing young people today and in the future will be
the focus of deliberations when representatives of some 140
nations gather in Lisbon from 8 to 12 August, UN Department of
Public Information said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This high-level meeting, convened by the Government of Portugal
and the United Nations and the first World Conference of Ministers
Responsible for youth, is the culminating event of more than a
decade-long process undertaken to turn the attention of national
and global leaders to the matters of importance to young people.
</P>
<P>
The international movement began during the 1985 international
Youth Year with the General Assembly's adoption of a global agenda
in support of national youth policies. Then in 1995, the General
Assembly adopted the World Program of Action for Youth to the
Year 2000 and Beyond, which clearly defines strategies and targets
for youth-related actions.
</P>
<P>
The world's youth -- people between 15 and 24 years old -- make
up nearly one fifth of the population. They are more than 1
billion people, mostly living in developing nations, striving to
be healthy, educated and active participants in their communities.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day conference, participants will decide on
further ways that governments and society can respond more
effectively to the economic, social, educational, emotional,
cultural and spiritual needs of young people.
</P>
<P>
The most visible goal for delegates to the world conference is
to finalize and then adopt a declaration by which their
governments would commit to fortify national policies to benefits
their youthful populations.
</P>
<P>
States would agree to enhance youth participation in all
spheres of society; ensure the right to development of all young
people; strengthen the role of youth in peace-building, conflict
prevention and conflict resolution; promote education, full
employment and health; and address drug and substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
The conference, in additional to being the first international
meeting of ministers of youth, is the first conference to be held
by a Member State in coordination with the United Nations. Under
this new cost-saving measure, all expenses are being borne
entirely by the Government of Portugal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980806.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-05 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Approves Budget for 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's National Assembly on
Wednesday approved a 4.35 billion Kuwaiti dinars (14.36 billion
U.S. dollars) budget for the fiscal year 1998-99 starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
The budget projected state revenues at 2.44 billion dinars
(8.06 billion dollars), and deficit at 2.16 billion dinars (7.13
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues were estimated at 1.89 billion dinars (6.24
billion dollars) and non-oil revenues at 550 million dinars (1.82
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, over 244 million dinars (806 million dollars) will go
to the Fund for Future Generations, which was designed to prepare
for the time when Kuwait's oil passes its heyday.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency, the budget was passed
with change by a vote of 33-0, with one abstention.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich Gulf country was hit hard by sliding oil prices on
the world market, which leads to a more than 50 percent increase
in budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Net deficit for the fiscal year 1987-88 was set at 1.27 billion
dinars (4.2 billion dollars) while the total budget was 4.38
billion dinars (14.45 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, up to 1.35 dinars (4.46 billion
dollars) goes for salaries, and 316.5 million dinars (1.04 billion
dollars) for services and commodities requirements.
</P>
<P>
Transportation, equipment and installations will receive 38
million dinars (1.25 billion dollars) while 434.5 million dinars
(1.43 billion dollars) is earmarked for structural projects,
maintenance and public ownerships.
</P>
<P>
As much as 2.24 billion dinars (7.42 billion dollars) is for
various expenditures and transfer payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
