<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn, Washington in Dispute over Return of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A German official Wednesday
dismissed U.S. accusations that the Bonn government was forcing
back Bosnian refugees living in the country for political
considerations ahead of Germany's general elections in September
this year.
</P>
<P>
The return of Bosnian war refugees living in Germany was
running according to plan and had in no way been speeded up, said
Germany's envoy for Bosnian refugee affair, Dietmar Schlee,
Wednesday in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Of the 85,000 Bosnian refugees who left Germany in the first
seven months of this year, only about 1,200 had been expelled,
Schlee said. "There are no mass expulsions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Germany has taken in a total of 350,000 Bosnian refugees since
the Bosnian civil war broke out in 1992. About 140,000 of those
refugees are still living in Germany currently, according to
Schlee.
</P>
<P>
The consistent return of refugees was also good for Bosnia's
reconstruction, Schlee said, adding that German authorities and
humanitarian organizations were now active in about 80 projects in
Bosnia to help rebuild the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on condition of anonymity, a senior U.S. government
official told the German news agency DPA on Tuesday that Germany's
"coercive" repatriation of refugees from the former Yugoslavia
threatened to destroy the hard-won Bosnian peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also linked Bonn's hardline policy to the upcoming German
national elections on September 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. special envoy for the former Yugoslavia, Robert
Gelbard, also told DPA that Washington was prepared to work with
Germany in the period after the September election to work out a
managed repatriation program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
